{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 1. Introduction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Welcome to Chaosium\u8217's Basic Roleplaying system, one of most influential roleplaying game systems in the world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you\u8217're familiar with roleplaying games you can skip through much of this introduction. This covers the terms used in the {\i Basic Roleplaying} system. For veteran players, the only section in this introduction you should pay attention to is the {\i Optional Rules} section.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Terms Used in Basic Roleplaying\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following terms are used frequently in this book. Some are common in roleplaying games, and are provided as an aid to new and experienced gamers alike. Each is explained at length in relevant sections.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ability:} Something a character can do or feel, whether a skill, a passion, or some other factor rated on a 1\u8211-100 rating. Generally when you roll an ability successfully, you get an experience check.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Allegiance:} An optional system measuring devotion to a spiritual being, principle, or deity, improved by performing favored actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Augment:} Using one ability to modify the chance of success using another ability, such as when one skill provides additional support to another, or a passion can help improve the chance of a skill succeeding.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} The default chance at succeeding with a skill a character has no training or experience in.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i on the character sheet, Hide (20%) means that even if your character has not invested any skill points in the Hide skill, they have a 20% natural ability in it.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Range:} The normal distance within which a missile weapon can hit a target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Character:} The role you assume in a game session, described in game mechanics by values such as characteristics and skill totals. Generally, characters have names and backgrounds determined by the player, with assistance and/or approval from the gamemaster. (see also {\b player character} and {\b nonplayer character}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Characteristic:} Your character\u8217's physical, mental, and spiritual attributes (Strength, Constitution, Size, Intelligence, Power, Dexterity, and Charisma), rated numerically on a scale (usually 3\u8211-18), with a human average being 10-11.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if the initial maximum characteristic is 18, a STR 17 means your character is extremely strong, while a DEX 7 means they are a bit clumsy.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Characteristic Roll:} One of your character\u8217's characteristics multiplied by a number (Intelligence \u215 ?3, for example), expressed as a percentage, and rolled with percentile dice. A characteristic roll is usually \u215 ?5, but other multiples may be used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if your character\u8217's Intelligence characteristic is 14, they have a 42% chance at succeeding with a characteristic check with a multiple of \u215 ?3.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Combat Round:} A 12-second (or equivalent) amount of time imposed during combat or dramatic activities, where the order that actions occur is important. This is game time, not actual time\u8212-the events of a few seconds of action may take several minutes to play out between the players and gamemaster.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Critical Success:} This is the result of a skill check roll that is 1/20 (or 5%) of the regular chance of success. Generally, a critical success is rewarded with greater results, though in some cases a critical success is required for success at all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if the regular chance for success is 75%, any roll of 4 or under is a critical success (1/20 of 75% is 3.75, rounded up to 4).}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b D100:} A percentile die roll, attained by rolling two 10-sided dice (D10s), with one representing the tens, and the other the ones. Some dice come already marked as \u8216'tens\u8217' (00, 10, 20, etc.) and are always used as the first number in a D100 roll. A roll of 01 is the best possible result, while 100 (which usually reads as 00) is the worst.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a roll of 60 (or 6) and 2 equals a result of 62.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Damage:} A value representing injury, subtracted from a character\u8217's hit points. Weapons, unfortunate events, and other hazards inflict damage on characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Damage Modifier:} A modifier to rolled damage due to above-average Strength and Size characteristics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b DEX Rank:} Based on the Dexterity characteristic, this determines when your character can usually act during a combat round. Characters with higher DEX will generally act before characters with lower DEX.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Difficulty Modifier:} The amount a skill\u8217's chance is adjusted by, based on the circumstances surrounding its use. These range from {\i Automatic} (no roll required), {\i Easy} (skill is doubled), {\i Average} (no modification to skill), and {\i Difficult} (skill is halved) to {\i Impossible} (no roll, or a 01% chance at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Experience Rolls:} If you are successful with a roll for one or more of your character\u8217's abilities or characteristic resistance rolls (see below), you should mark your character sheet in the provided check box (sometimes this action is called an \u8220"experience check\u8221"), if appropriate. Later, between adventures or during down-time, you can determine if your character\u8217's ability has improved in that skill or if the characteristic has increased through successful use. Some skills cannot be improved by experience and must be improved through other means.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fail:} A roll of percentile dice above the required chance for success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a roll of 89 when the required chance was 56% indicates a failure.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fatal Wound:} A wound that costs your character more hit points than they currently possess. Without intervention (medical or otherwise) death comes at the end of the following combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fatigue Points:} An optional system, using your character\u8217's Strength and Constitution characteristic to determine how long they can endure strenuous physical activity before tiring.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Full Turn:} A period consisting of 25 combat rounds, equaling five minutes of game world time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fumble:} A roll of 99 and/or 00 when rolling percentile dice to determine success. Generally, when a fumble is indicated something bad happens above and beyond a simple failure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gamemaster (GM):} The director, or guide for the game, who helps you create characters, comes up with the adventure, and represents the world outside your character, rolling dice for the nonplayer characters and the opposing forces.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Game Time:} The time that elapses as a scenario or campaign unfolds as experienced by your characters. This is not usually the same as the real time you and the gamemaster spend playing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hit Location:} An optional system for specifying where a successful attack lands on your character\u8217's body, or where their attacks hit a foe.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hit Points:} A measure of the relative health of your character, represented in a value derived from their Constitution and Size characteristics. Attackers inflict damage in hit points, subtracted from the target\u8217's total hit points. Usually when your character reaches 0 hit points, they are dead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b \u8220"In character\u8221" or \u8220"Out of character\u8221":} The distinction in the chat between players and the gamemaster around the gaming table, representing the difference between real-world discussion and game discussion. Both achieve the same goal, but represent different styles or aspects of play, and can be used interchangeably in play. Some groups or players lean towards one or another\u8212-it\u8217's an element of preference. \u8220"In character\u8221" discussion is flavorful and immersive, while \u8220"out of character\u8221" discussion is essential to describe rules mechanics and to speed along play through unnecessary detail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i in character, you might say \u8216'Sir Wilfric asks the innkeeper \u8220"Could you perhaps allow us the night\u8217's stay for a promise of future payment!\u8221"\u8217' while out of character, you might say \u8220"I try to Persuade the innkeeper to let us stay a night without pay.\u8221"}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Magic Points:} Another name for power points (see {\b power points}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major Wound:} An injury causing enough damage to exceed half the character\u8217's normal hit point total in a single blow. Usually accompanied by a debilitating effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Wound:} Any single injury that is less than a major wound in severity (less than 1/2 normal hit points).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Modifiers:} Temporary additions or subtractions to your character\u8217's rating in an ability, usually from circumstances, environment, or equipment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i trying to pick a lock with a bent paper clip is an example of substandard tools, for a \u8211-20% modifier. Using a standard lockpick does not modify the skill. Using a deluxe set of calibrated precision lockpicks and lockpicking equipment adds +20% to your character\u8217's skill rating.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Move (MOV):} The rate of movement your character can make during a single combat round. This measurement is a flexible one, but usually translates to one meter of unhurried movement per point of MOV.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Nonplayer Character (NPC):} A character or creature in the game world that is played or otherwise represented by the gamemaster, instead of being played by you or another player.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Opposed Roll:} When your character wants to attempt an action another character (or nonplayer character) wants to oppose with an \u8220"opposite\u8221" skill that cancels or thwarts the initial action. In this case, both skill checks are made, and the results compared.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i Stealth is usually opposed by Listen.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Passion:} An optional system where a strongly held belief towards a subject\u8212-such as Devotion, Fear, Hate, Love, Loyalty\u8212-is measured on a percentile basis. Passions are used to indicate or determine how your character feels about the subject and how strongly, and is often used to augment ability rolls. (see {\b augments}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Percentile Dice:} Two D10s rolled together, with one designated as the tens figure, and the other as ones. Some dice are numbered in units of ten, i.e., 00, 10, 20, 30, etc. See also {\b D100}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Player Character (PC):} This is your character, usually created and almost always controlled by you, comprised of abilities and an identity you assume through roleplaying. Your character is your representation in the game world and enables you to interact with the setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power:} A generic term for magic spells, mutations, psychic abilities, sorcery, or super abilities your character may possess (see {\i Chapter 4: Powers}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Points:} The amount of willpower or energy your character has, represented as a total based on their Power characteristic. These are spent to use special powers or abilities and can be drained by other abilities. When your character reaches 0 power points, they fall unconscious. Power points can also be called {\b magic points} in appropriate genres.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Profession:} Your character\u8217's job occupation, represented as a list of skills they have been trained to use (or have had the opportunity to learn).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rating:} The chance of success for an ability, rated as value from 1\u8211-100 (sometimes higher).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i Demolitions 43% is a rating of 43, meaning a 43% chance of success when the skill is attempted during normal circumstances. (see also {\b skill rating}).}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance Roll:} When your character wants to attempt an action being resisted by an inanimate object or force, the relevant characteristic (for example, Strength) is opposed to another appropriate characteristic (for example, the stuck door\u8217's Strength). The two numbers are cross-referenced on the resistance table (see below) to determine a chance of success, and one or both characters roll dice to see who succeeds. Equal characteristics mean a 50% chance of success. Resistance rolls can also be used when pitting one character against another character, such as an arm-wrestling match (Strength vs.\u160 ?Strength).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance Table:} The table showing the ratio of characteristic versus characteristic. To use the resistance table, find the opposing force on the vertical column, the resisting force on the horizontal column, then cross-reference them to find the likelihood of success, expressed as a percentile chance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Roll:} A roll using D100 to determine whether an attempt at performing a skill, ability, or power was successful. The result of a skill roll is a {\b critical success}, {\b special success}, {\b success}, {\b failure}, or a {\b fumble}. Additional means of determining the quality of success are presented in optional rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sanity:} An optional system where your character\u8217's mental health is measured by their capacity to withstand horrific sights, events, and revelations. As Sanity gets lower, the grasp on reality diminishes. If your character loses too much Sanity at once, they can go temporarily or permanently insane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill:} An ability, training, field of knowledge, talent, specialty, or something your character knows something about (or is talented in), quantified as a skill level. Skills are used in skill rolls, where percentile dice are rolled against the skill\u8217's rating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Rating:} The degree of competence your character has with a skill, expressed as a number from 00% (no skill whatsoever) to 100% or higher (world-class expert).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Special Success:} A roll of 1/5 of the required score for success indicates that your character performed exceptionally well and achieves a superior result than a traditional success. This is especially significant in combat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a character with 70% in a skill who rolls 14 or lower has achieved a special success.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Success:} The result of a percentage dice roll where your character performed the task adequately, and achieved an average quality of success. If the roll is very low, it may be a {\b special success} or {\b critical success}, as described above. If it is above the ability ranking, it is usually a {\b failure}. If it is very high, such as a 00, it might be a {\b fumble}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if your character has a 70% in a skill, and rolls 70 or lower, they have succeeded.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Optional Rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Over the years, various sub-systems were introduced into Basic Roleplaying games to cover situations or conditions suitable to the specific game, such as expanded combat systems for fantasy games, rules for insanity and research for horror games, rules for the use of vehicles and spaceships, rules governing grand passions and personality traits, different magic systems appropriate to the genre, etc. Core elements have even been changed or treated differently, sometimes even in different editions of the same game.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These variations appear here as optional rules, presented in boxes like this one, with suggestions about when to use them, and notes about how they affect play, and in some cases, about how they interact with other optional rules. Thus, the gamemaster can pick and choose optional rules as desired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before you begin play, you should decide what sorts of optional rules you want to use, especially those that apply to character creation. {\i Chapter 10: Settings} suggests what optional rules go well with particular settings, and additionally, a complete list is presented in {\i Chapter 9: Gamemastering}. # 2. Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Put simply, your {\b character} is {\b you} in the game world, the persona you play in the game. The character is the focus of all roleplaying games\u8212-an abstraction of physical and mental abilities, skills, and other descriptors. You interact with your gamemaster in that world through your character. Most characters controlled by players are {\b player characters} (PCs).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster describes the setting, the environment, and the encounters to the players. Your gamemaster has at their disposal a roster of other characters, called {\b nonplayer characters} (NPCs). Both player and nonplayer characters use the same rules, though generally nonplayer characters are less detailed than player characters, as NPCs rarely face the same variety of situations player characters do.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Chapter 11: Creatures} describes how your gamemaster can create appropriate nonplayer characters and includes a roster of ready-to-use nonplayer characters (as well as monsters and other creatures) for a variety of settings and eras. This section deals with player characters and is essential reading for you and your gamemaster alike.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When a \u8220"character\u8221" is mentioned, the term applies to player characters and nonplayer characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Power Level\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Throughout this chapter and elsewhere in the rules are references to the game\u8217's power level. This describes how reasonably competent the player and nonplayer characters are, and where on a scale from \u8220"realistic\u8221" to \u8220"mythical\u8221" gameplay will feel like.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are four game power levels, described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Normal\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters have no powers or very few, unreliable powers. Sometimes characters are defined by a single power, barely more than an extraordinary talent. This is the most suitable power level for horror or modern adventure games, where technology and wits are often the decisive factor in survival.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Heroic\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters have a few strong powers or a wide range of mid- to low-level powers. This is suitable for games featuring inexperienced, costumed heroes or apprentice wizards in training, the mutated survivors of a radioactive apocalypse, vigilante heroes, or a high fantasy world of wizards and warriors. Some futuristic settings might be created using this power level, with citizens having many minor powers granted by genetic manipulation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Epic\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters are incredibly skilled or powered, such as arch-mages, or formidable supernatural beings. Sample games might be full of veteran costumed heroes or villains, or veteran supernatural heroes fighting the forces of darkness in the shadows of the modern world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Superhuman\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These characters have immense capabilities and are the mightiest of heroes. Games might feature extraordinarily powered costumed superheroes, galactic guardians, or even modern incarnations of great demigods.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster should make it clear to you and your fellow players what power level your game is, to set expectations and to guide the rest of character creation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Creating a Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You first need a character. Following is a system for developing your character. This system creates reasonably competent characters. Suggestions are provided in each step for more powerful characters. You should have a blank character sheet handy, and maybe another sheet of paper for notes. At chaosium.com you can download digital versions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you get ready to create your character, your gamemaster and the other players should have already decided what sort of game you\u8217'll all play, whether it be a science fiction, fantasy, modern horror, historical intrigue, espionage, pulp action, techno-thriller, or any number of other genres.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster should be prepared to guide you and the other players through the character creation process, knowing what professions are allowed and appropriate to the game or campaign, and what level of competency the characters should exhibit. These issues are most important to {\b Step Seven} and may influence {\b Step Three}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step One: Name and Characteristics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Write your character\u8217's name at the top of the page. This should be appropriate to the setting and game being played. If no idea suggests itself yet, wait until later. You can write your own name on the character sheet as your gamemaster may need to keep track of which character belongs to whom.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Choose your character\u8217's gender and write it in the correct space.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Roll 3D6 for the characteristics Strength (STR), Constitution (CON), Power (POW), Dexterity (DEX), and Charisma (CHA). Enter the results in the appropriate places on your character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Roll 2D6+6 for the Intelligence (INT) and Size (SIZ) characteristics.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These numbers provide the bare bones of your character, determining what characteristics the character is strong or weak in.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If you wish, redistribute up to 3 points between your characteristics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab No characteristic can begin at more than 21 points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If you aren\u8217't satisfied with the characteristics you have, and your gamemaster approves, you can start over.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the campaign is using one or more types of powers, your gamemaster may allow you to increase your starting characteristics (see {\i Chapter 4: Powers}, particularly {\b Diminish/Enhance Characteristic}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Choosing Characteristic Values (Option):} Traditionally, characteristics are rolled in order, with up to 3 points redistributed. Instead, you may roll 3D6 seven times and choose where results go. In this case, SIZ and INT cannot be below 8.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Higher Starting Characteristics (Option):} For a higher-powered game, roll 2D6+6 for all characteristics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Education (EDU) Characteristic (Option):} Roll 2D6+6 for Education (EDU) for this characteristic, for characters from societies with formalized education. An EDU of 12 indicates a high school graduate-level education, with higher values indicating college or advanced degrees.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Cultural Modifiers (Option):} Cultural modifiers emphasize characteristic differences between different species (such as elves or dwarves) or for different human cultures. Initial characteristics may be adjusted or limited at this point. See {\b Cultural Characteristic Modifiers (Option)}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Non-human Characters (Option):} Non-human characters may use different dice rolls and modifiers to determine initial characteristics. See {\i Chapter 11: Creatures}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Point-based Character Creation (Option):} Usually, characteristics are rolled randomly. Instead, players can purchase characteristic points from a pool. See {\b Point-based Character Creation (Option)}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step Two: Powers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Read this carefully! If the game you\u8217're playing in involves magic, mutations, psychic abilities, sorcery, or superpowers you may begin with some of these powers. Ask your gamemaster about it and refer to {\i Chapter 4: Powers} for more information. These systems require more explanation than is provided in this chapter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there are no powers in the campaign, ignore this step and proceed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there are powers, the following types are available:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Magic:} Simple spellcasting with a wide variety of applications.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Mutations:} Strange genetic anomalies, some beneficial, some adverse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Psychic Abilities:} Using the power of the mind to manipulate reality.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sorcery:} A more baroque type of spellcasting, including elemental and demonic summoning.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Superpowers:} Mighty abilities that defy imagination.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 More detail on each appears in their relevant sections.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step Three: Age\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default age for characters is 17+1D6 years old. Your gamemaster may choose to alter this based on the requirements of the game setting. If you wish to begin play with a character younger or older, choose an age that seems appropriate and meets your gamemaster\u8217's approval.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For every full 10 years added to the rolled starting age, based on the level of the campaign, modify professional skill points by +0 (Normal), +20 (Heroic), +30 (Epic), or +40 (Superhuman) (see {\b Step Seven}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any fraction of years below 10 does not qualify for this skill bonus. Based on level of campaign, for every year below the minimum age (18) described above, subtract 0 (Normal), 20 (Heroic), 30 (Epic), or 40 skill points (Superhuman) from your character\u8217's professional skill points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your gamemaster may limit available professions to characters below 18 years of age.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab At age 50 and every full 10 years above, modify one of STR, CON, DEX, or CHA (your choice) by \u8211-1. At age 80 and every full 10 years above, modify {\b three} of these characteristics. See {\b Aging and Inaction (Option)}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For every year below the original rolled age above, modify any one characteristic other than EDU (your choice) by \u8211-1. Your gamemaster may require that you make SIZ one of these lowered characteristics. These points can be gained through play (experience), training, or gradually through natural means (gamemaster\u8217's discretion). See {\b Aging and Inaction (Option)}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster may also choose to simply ignore these rules, based on the game\u8217's power level. This allows for elderly adventurers, child geniuses, and is generally more enjoyable for all players.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Education (EDU) (Option):} If you\u8217're using the EDU characteristic, your character\u8217's starting age must be at least EDU+5 (representing time spent learning). Every full 10 years added to your character\u8217's starting age, adds +1 to your character\u8217's EDU characteristic. Be sure to increase the relevant skill points generated in {\b Step Six}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step Four: Characteristic Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here\u8217's where you determine your characteristic rolls. By now you should know what your final characteristics are, but if not, hold off on this step until you\u8217've finalized them. Each has a place on the character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply STR\u215 ?5 for your Effort roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply CON\u215 ?5 for your Stamina roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply INT\u215 ?5 for your Idea roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply POW\u215 ?5 for your Luck roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply DEX\u215 ?5 for your Agility roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Multiply CHA\u215 ?5 for your Charm roll.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knowledge Roll (Option):} Multiply EDU\u215 ?5 for your Knowledge roll (if EDU is being used).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step Five: Derived Characteristics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now it\u8217's time for the derived characteristics: damage modifier, hit points, power points and experience bonus. If you\u8217're using optional systems, you should also determine your initial fatigue points and sanity points. Write the results on your character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Damage Modifier: Add STR+SIZ and find the {\b damage modifier} corresponding to your character\u8217's total on the {\b Damage Modifier} table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Hit Points:} Add CON+SIZ and divide by 2 (rounded up). Circle that number in the {\b Hit Points} box on your character sheet and write it below. This is your character\u8217's maximum hit points. If your character loses hit points, mark them off, and erase the marks as hit points are healed or otherwise restored.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Major Wound Level:} Your {\b major wound level} is 1/2 hit points, rounded up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Power Points:} In the {\b Power Point} box, circle the number equal to POW and write the total on the line below. This is your character\u8217's maximum power points. These fuel magic spells, mutations, psychic abilities, or superpowers. Mark power points off as they\u8217're spent and erase the marks as they\u8217're recovered or otherwise restored. The number written in the space, equal to your POW, is the value your power points return to with rest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Experience Bonus:} Your character\u8217's experience bonus is equal to 1/2 their INT, rounded up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Move (MOV):} Your character\u8217's MOV measures how fast during a combat round they can move. Human characters can normally move 10 units per round. A unit is a somewhat variable amount usually equaling 1 meter. See {\b Movement Rates}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Bonuses (Option):} If using characteristic-based skill category bonuses, calculate the bonus for each using the Skill {\b Category Bonus} table. Write these values in the spaces for each category. This bonus adds to the base chance for every skill, if any. For each category:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add +1% for every point in the primary characteristic over 10; subtract 1% for every point below 10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab +1% for every 2 points in the secondary characteristic above 10; \u8211-1% for every 2 points under 10 (rounding down the bonus if required).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab \u8211-1% for every point in the negative characteristic above 10; +1% for every point under 10.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hit Points per Location (Option):} With the optional hit location system, determine the number of hit points for each hit location. The head, abdomen, and each leg have 1/3 of your hit point total, the chest has 4/10, and each arm has 1/4 of the total hit point value. Round all fractions up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fatigue Points (Option):} If fatigue is being used; add your character\u8217's STR+CON to get their fatigue point total. In play, as your character expends energy or perform rigorous physical activity, they will lose fatigue points. They recover rapidly through rest and other means and change frequently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sanity (Option):} If Sanity is being used; multiply your character\u8217's initial POW score by \u215 ?5 to get their current Sanity (SAN) total. In play, mark these off on your character sheet when your character loses sanity points. When your character reaches 0 SAN, they are considered unplayable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Step Six: Personality (Optional)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Study your character\u8217's characteristics and imagine the sort of person you would like them to be. Choose one of the options below or roll 1D4 for a random result. These packages of skills are a quick way to develop your character\u8212-there will be more skills in the next step. Skills are defined in {\i Chapter 3: Skills} 37\u8211-52 and classes of weapons are described in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}.\par}
