{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The sum of your character\u8217's hit points by location exceeds their maximum hit points, but whenever a character is wounded, the rolled damage is subtracted from both that location\u8217's hit point total and your character\u8217's maximum hit points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Damage exceeding a location\u8217's total hit points renders it useless. Damage equal to twice a location\u8217's hit point total crushes or severs it. See {\b Damage per Hit Location}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b For example,} {\i your character has 14 hit points, with 5 hit points in each leg, 5 hit points in the abdomen, 6 hit points in the chest, 4 hit points in each arm, and 5 hit points in their head. Even though their hit points in all locations total 34, your character will die if they suffer a total of 14 hit points of damage.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b Major Wound} system is not easily compatible with the hit location system and should a gamemaster choose to use the optional hit locations and {\b Damage by Hit Location} systems, the major wound system should be eliminated or adapted considerably, perhaps with the nature of the major wound being chosen by your gamemaster where applicable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Major Wounds (1/2 of HP)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Divide your character\u8217's hit point total in half, rounding up if necessary. This total is their major wound level. If your character takes this amount of damage from a single wound, they may suffer horrific side-effects as well as simple hit point loss. See** Major Wound**s in {\i Chapter 6: Combat}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Power Points (Max = POW)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Power points (PP) represent your character\u8217's vital essence, their reserves of spiritual or life energy. Your character spends power points to cast or resist spells. Your character\u8217's maximum power points are usually equal to their POW characteristic. Generally, spent power points regenerate at a rate of 1 per hour of sleep or total rest, or 1 for every two hours of normal activity. See the {\b Power Point Recovery Rate Table} for rates for higher POW scores. If your character is engaged in strenuous activity, they cannot regain power points. When your character\u8217's power point total falls to 0, they are completely exhausted, and faint until regaining at least 1 power point. You cannot have negative power points.\par}
