{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike hit points or fatigue points, power points can climb above the maximum for brief times under certain conditions. As noted, if your character receives additional power points (usually through the use of a power), they can store up to twice their POW characteristic in extra power points. Any power points beyond that are lost. If your character uses any power points while over their normal maximum, these must come from the extra power points first. These extra power points are not renewed and do not regenerate as normal and dissipate entirely after a night\u8217's sleep or a suitable juncture determined by your gamemaster.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Items that store power points and allow the wielder to use the stored power points do not count against this total, as long as the power points are not stored in the user\u8217's own power point reserve. In most cases, the power points are used straight from the item\u8217's reserve, and do not affect the user\u8217's own power points. See Chapter 8: Equipment for more on items with power point reservoirs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Other Kinds of Power Points (Option)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Due to the variety of powers in {\i Chapter 4: Powers}, \u8220"power points\u8221" is used in place of other names like \u8220"temporary power\u8221" or \u8220"magic points.\u8221". If desired, your gamemaster can change the name to \u8220"energy points\u8221" or \u8220"magic points\u8221" or whatever is appropriate to the setting. If systems other than magic or sorcery are used, it is recommended to keep them called power points, to avoid confusion. It is advised not to use two different names for power points in the same game.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Movement (MOV)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All human and humanoid characters begin with a movement (MOV) attribute of 10. This measures how much distance your character can move in a combat round. A unit is a flexible distance, and can range from 1\u8211-5 meters, depending on how quickly your character is moving.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A walk is 1 meter per MOV.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A run is up to 5 meters per MOV.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab An average rate of movement in combat is 3 meters (yards) per unit, meaning that on average, your character moves 30 meters a combat round.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Movement rates are described further in {\b Movement Rates} in {\i Chapter 5: System}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Fatigue Points and Sanity Points (Option)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some optional systems and powers refer to fatigue points and sanity points. For a more detailed encumbrance and fatigue system, your gamemaster should use fatigue points (described below). Games based on horror, blasphemous sorcery, or indescribable atrocity will depend heavily on the use of the sanity system (also below).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Fatigue Points (Max = STR + CON)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fatigue points} (FP) measure your character\u8217's endurance, such as how long they can engage in strenuous activity before exhaustion sets in. Your character\u8217's maximum fatigue points are equal to their STR+CON. Your character expends 1 fatigue point per combat round of strenuous activity (melee combat, swimming, sprinting, climbing, etc.). Sprinting or backbreaking labor costs 1 fatigue point per turn. Forced marches cost 1 fatigue point per hour. Unlike hit points and power points, your character can continue to act with negative fatigue points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When your character drops below 0 fatigue points, they suffer a penalty of \u8211-1% per negative point of fatigue to all skill, characteristic, and resistance rolls. When your character\u8217's negative fatigue point total equals their base fatigue value (STR+CON), they are incapacitated by exhaustion, incapable of action. An exhausted character may fall unconscious (gamemaster discretion), and even if they remain awake, they cannot act until their fatigue point value regenerates to a positive number. Your character\u8217's encumbrance value (ENC) also affects their base fatigue value. See {\b Encumbrance}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character regains 1 fatigue point every minute (5 rounds) where they do not spend fatigue points. Resting, walking at a slow pace, or riding a beast or vehicle does not expend fatigue. An average character recovers from 0 to their full fatigue point total in 20 minutes (assuming a STR 10, CON 10, and 1 fatigue point recovered per minute of rest).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Simple Fatigue\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For a simpler version of fatigue eliminates fatigue points altogether, your gamemaster may declare that after some massive endeavor or extreme physical hardship, your character is fatigued. They are either ready for action, or they are fatigued. Your gamemaster may allow a Stamina roll to escape being fatigued after a period of physical exertion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Using this method, your character grow tired after spending CON\u215 ?3 uninterrupted combat rounds in battle or difficult physical activity. After that, your character is automatically fatigued, and all skill rolls are {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After spending CON\u215 ?4 uninterrupted combat rounds in battle or difficult physical activity, your character makes all their skills as if they were 1/4 the normal skill rating and must make a successful Stamina roll to do anything physical before the skill rating can even be attempted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After CON\u215 ?10 rounds of such activity, your character is utterly exhausted, and is barely able to lift their weapon, stand upright without something to lean on, etc. At this point, your character must make a {\i Difficult} Stamina roll to do any basic action, and your gamemaster may rule that any skill roll is {\i Impossible} or limited to your character\u8217's POW\u215 ?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Sanity Points (Max = POW\u215 ?5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As described in {\b Sanity} (see {\i Chapter 10: Settings}), {\b sanity points} (SAN) represent your character\u8217's mental and emotional fortitude, and their ability to withstand shock, terror, and cosmic awfulness. Your character\u8217's base SAN points equal their POW\u215 ?5.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Whenever your character is exposed to a horrifying situation or mind-bending strangeness, they must roll D100 against their current SAN point total. If your character fails (or perhaps even if they succeed) they lose sanity points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A character who suffers sufficient SAN loss will likely go mad. Your character\u8217's {\b temporary insanity score} (like a Major Wound Threshold) equals \u189 ? their current SAN. Losing this many SAN points in a five-minute period results in some form of temporary insanity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sanity points do not naturally regenerate and can only be recovered under very specific circumstances. Characters can gain SAN beyond their base value, to a maximum of 99. Certain types of blasphemous knowledge can limit a character\u8217's maximum allowable SAN score.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Distinctive Features (Option)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Distinctive features are a way of describing notable features about your character. These are descriptive only and have no mechanical value. They serve to help make your player character seem more real. The further from average\u8212-higher or lower\u8212-your character\u8217's Charisma (CHA) characteristic, the greater number of distinctive features they have.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Distinctive Features\par}
