{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Augments and Complementary skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some skills are closely related to others, and expertise in one field can benefit another. With your gamemaster\u8217's permission, your character may temporarily add 1/5 of your rating in a {\b complementary skill} to your rating in another skill for skill rolls. Many complementary uses are noted in the skill descriptions that follow. You and the other players will doubtless devise more.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Only one skill may be complementary to another when used to assist any given roll. If multiple skills may be applicable or are used to try to get this bonus, the benefits do not stack\u8212-the player and gamemaster should choose the highest bonus to use, or whichever is most appropriate to the situation at hand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the main skill roll is a success, your character receives an experience check only to the main skill, not to the complementary skill used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i your character has a Medicine skill of 65% and a Science (Pharmacy) of 40%. They are attempting to treat a diseased patient. As long as your character has sufficient medical supplies and medications available, they can add 8% (1/5 of their Science(Pharmacy) rating) to the Medicine skill rating, for a modified rating of 73%. Your character cannot add 1/5 of his First Aid or Science (Biology) skill on top of the Pharmacy bonus. In this case, the gamemaster rules that the Science (Pharmacy)skill is the most appropriate for the bonus.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An {\b augment} to a skill is similar but works in a slightly different fashion. If your gamemaster permits it, you can attempt a roll of one complementary skill to support , or augment, another primary skill roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the augmenting skill roll is successful, you may adjust the difficulty of the primary skill by one step, such as turning a {\i Difficult} roll into an {\i Average} one, or an {\i Average} task {\i Easy}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This cannot be done simultaneously with a complementary skill bonus, however, and only one degree of adjustment is possible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the augment fails, the primary skill is adjusted by one step the opposite direction, such as a {\i Normal} skill becoming {\i Difficult} due to confusion or conflicting information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If successful with the augmenting skill roll, you may check it for experience as normal, as well as with the primary skill. If the primary roll fails, the augmenting skill does not receive an experience check.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You cannot augment a skill and use a complementary skill bonus simultaneously for the same skill roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Skill Ratings Above 100%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character\u8217's experience bonus makes it possible to raise skill ratings above 100%. Skills higher than 100% use the standard systems to compute the chances of special or critical successes, as well as offering better odds of success at {\i Difficult} tasks or in the face of negative circumstantial modifiers. Additionally, if your character has a combat skill higher than 100%, they can take multiple attacks in a combat round, as described in {\b Attacks and Parries Over 100%}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Describing Results of Successes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Generally, the results of skill rolls are obvious, but if in doubt, use the following guidelines when determining outcomes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A {\b fumble} usually means that the opposite of the desired result has been achieved, providing misleading information, creating some sort of setback, or even putting the character at a disadvantage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure} means that the desired result is not achieved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A normal {\b success} means that a reasonable and average goal has been achieved. The gamemaster is the ultimate arbiter of the results, but the effect should be obvious.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A {\b special success} has double the effectiveness of a regular success and/or provides additional information about the subject.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A {\b critical succes}s has triple the effectiveness of a regular success, and/or provides considerable information about the subject.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As noted above, skills where outcomes are very specific and where detail is required, have retained the defined result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Skill Descriptions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A comprehensive, alphabetical list of skills follows. Each entry contains the following information:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skill Name:} The name of the skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Base Chance:} The skill rating all characters have in the skill, specialized by era if applicable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Category:} The skill category the skill falls into, for purposes of general classification and optional category bonuses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Description:} A brief description of the kinds of tasks that can be accomplished using the skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Specialties:} A listing of the skill\u8217's distinct specialties, if any. Not all skills with specialties have them elaborated upon in a bulleted list\u8212-only those that are more mechanical in nature, such as Combat skills, are detailed in this manner.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Effects:} The results of a skill roll, for each degree of success, where required. In brief, a skill result is a fumble (the worst possible result, usually a roll of 99 or 00), a failure (a roll above your skill rating), a success (equal to or below your skill rating), a special success (1/5 or less of your skill rating), or a critical success (1/20 or less of your skill rating). {\i Chapter 5: System} explains this in detail. See also {\b Describing Results of Success}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Setting Notes:} Additional information about the skill in different settings. If this entry is not present, the skill works unchanged in almost any setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b System Notes:} Relevant rules or systems, if any.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Appraise\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 15%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to estimate an object\u8217's worth, be it an old painting, a gemstone, a weapon, or a riding horse. Failure means they have no idea, while a fumble yields false information. A special or critical yields additional information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Art (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to create a work of art in paint or sculpture, or to compose a story, poem, or musical work. A critical or special success yields a timeless classic of considerably more value and prestige, a failure is mediocre hackwork, and a fumble may harm the creator\u8217's reputation. You would use Perform for acting, dancing, singing, or playing a musical instrument.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Calligraphy, Composing, Conceptual Art, Digital Art, Drawing, Painting, Photography, Poetry, Sculpture, Sketching, Songwriting, Writing, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Art is universal, though it may have era- or setting-specific specialties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Artillery (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon specialty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to fire massive field pieces and heavy vehicular weapons, essentially any weapon too large for a single person to move or maneuver, such as a cannon, trebuchet, or ballista.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Specialties are equivalent to types. See {\b Artillery} in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for artillery types.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Missile Weapon Fumbles Table} for specific effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Suitable for many settings, ranging from siege engines to modern or futuristic artillery and vehicular weapons. In most settings, a military background is required to learn this skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Many large weapons require a crew to operate; attempting to use one alone is a {\i Difficult} action or may be {\i Impossible}. It may take multiple rounds or even turns to load and prepare a weapon system between shots. Many large weapons employ automatic fire or shoot explosive ordinance. See {\b Autofire} and {\b Explosion}. All shots go somewhere; the gamemaster should decide where missed explosive or energy shots impact.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Bargain\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to haggle over prices, and whenever opposing opinions meet in negotiation and compromise. Use opposed skill rolls to decide important deals, and simple skill rolls for trivial attempts (saving money on equipment or lodgings, for example). Bargaining is about compromise: use Fast Talk or Persuade to resolve arguments that are absolutely won or lost. A fumble might mean turn a merchant into an enemy, success means you get a deal, and better results yield higher discounts or more favorable conditions for your side.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Brawl\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill for unarmed combat: kicks, punches, head butts, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Natural Weapon Attack and Parry Fumbles Table}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Brawling can be used to parry (see Parry) but a successful parry inflicts minimum weapon damage on the parrying arm or leg, as appropriate. Using Brawl against a foe that has grappled your character (see Grapple) is {\i Easy}. Used in conjunction with Martial Arts and with the Natural Weapon and Unarmed Combat powers from {\i Chapter 4: Powers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Climb\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 40%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to climb up or down walls, trees, cliffs, or any other surface. Ample hand and footholds are assumed to be present: modify the difficulty based on conditions or the surface being climbed. Fumbling means you fall hard (see {\b Falling}), failing means you\u8217're stuck or you fall (gamemaster choice, based on circumstances), and superior successes let you climb faster and farther.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Generally, climbing is at 1/5 the MOV rate, and animals with natural climbing ability can move at their full MOV rate. Climbing ladders is {\i Automatic}. Very tall ladders or trees is {\i Easy}. Climbing without using your character\u8217's feet is {\i Difficult}. For extended climbs, the gamemaster should call for a skill roll once every minute, or 10 meters of climbing. Your character can take no other action while climbing, and all actions taken while clinging to a surface are {\i Difficult}, with any fumble causing a fall.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Command\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to inspire, direct, and coordinate subordinates, guiding them in complex tasks and improving the effectiveness of the group. Military officers, noblemen, politicians, and business executives are made or broken based on their ability to manage and lead. Personality, a strong voice, and an iron will are invaluable tools of command. A fumble incites insurrection, failing is uninspiring and confusing, and success allows you to add 1/5 your Command skill as a complementary skill bonus to all your subordinates for each round you command them, so long as they follow your orders. Roll every round in combat, or every turn in mass combat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Used primarily in combat, though it can extend to corporate negotiations, etc. Artillery, Heavy Weapon, Melee Weapon, Missile Weapon, and Strategy are the most appropriate skills to receive this benefit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Craft (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to construct or make things, from a chair to a meal to a house. Specialized tools are often required for this skill, and it takes time and raw materials. This skill can also be used to identify how an object was made, and possibly identify the crafter who made it. A fumble destroys the material and yields nothing useful, success means it works, and a better quality of success yields a finer, sturdier, or more valuable version of the thing being made, perhaps with additional qualities like a +10% or +20% to its efficacy when used, higher hit points, etc. This is about function and practicality: fashioning objects solely for aesthetical purposes falls under Art.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Blacksmithing, Carpentry, Ceramics, Cooking, Leatherworking, Locksmithing, Metallurgy, Stonemasonry, and others as appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Using Craft without the proper tools is {\i Difficult}. See {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for more information about making, modifying, or repairing equipment. Possession of a fine item of clothing or gear may even increase CHA while the item is worn or displayed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Demolition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to store, transport, set, and detonate explosives, from kegs of gunpowder to dynamite, Molotov cocktails, advanced plastic explosives, and anti-matter bombs. Anyone can simply set off a bomb: this is to achieve a specific effect with the explosion; collapse a building safely, destroy a bridge, or blow the door of a safe without harming the contents. Demolition also covers knowledge of appropriate accessories for explosives, including primer cord, fuses, and detonators. Use Science (Chemistry) to produce explosive compounds or Technical Skill to fashion other explosives. A fumble blows things up in your face, a failure means the desired effect is not achieved (a misfire or dud), and superior successes yield more impressive results, whether more damage, less collateral damage, special effects like Knockback, additional area of effect, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} With a skill rating of 60%+, normal uses of this skill automatically succeed. Unstable explosives (sweaty dynamite) may call for a Demolition every round they are being handled or used. Demolishing a massive structure (bridge, dam, bunker, or building) is {\i Difficult} unless your character has access to blueprints or plans of the target. Trying to use this skill without appropriate tools (fuses, etc.), or using explosives outside your character\u8217's normal field of expertise may be {\i Difficult} or even {\i Impossible}. Some types of explosives such as grenades might be used without this skill. See {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for explosives and their effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Disguise\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to employ posture, costume, voice, and other tricks to appear as a different person, or a different kind of person. Dim light, theatrical makeup, and significant facial alterations (a haircut or wig, false beards or a quick shave) can add up to a +20% bonus, at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion. Onlookers who scrutinize your disguised character or engage them in conversation can make and opposed Spot or Insight skill check against your character\u8217's Disguise roll to see through the ruse. Your disguised character can use their Fast Talk skill for the opposed check if they engage the onlooker in conversation, distracting them from close scrutiny. A fumble is blatantly obvious, a failure doesn\u8217't fool anyone who gives a second look, and superior successes may even add a complementary bonus to Communication rolls against those being fooled, or makes detection more difficult.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Using this skill to impersonate a particular kind of person (soldier, policeman, etc.) is a normal action. Impersonating someone vastly different (other species, alternate body type, another gender, etc.) or a specific well-known person (a noble, a celebrity, etc.), or attempting a disguise without appropriate clothing or props is {\i Difficult}. The gamemaster may assign additional penalties for cultural or language barriers, or if multiple {\i Difficult} conditions apply. Too much of a stretch may simply be {\i Impossible}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Dodge\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} DEX\u215 ?2\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The best defense in combat, as any combatant knows, is to not be there. Dodge allows your character to evade incoming attacks, using agility to avoid or minimize injury.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} A successful Dodge roll modifies the result of a successful attack, turning it into a failure. A special result for a Dodge roll modifies an attack two steps (a special success becomes a failure), and a critical success on a Dodge roll modifies a successful attack three steps (a critical attack becomes a failure). See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Natural Weapons Attack and Parry Fumbles Table} for specific effects. A successful Dodge roll cannot reduce an incoming attack\u8217's success lower than failure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} As described in {\b Dodge} in {\i Chapter 6: Combat}, your character may either Dodge or Parry in a combat round but cannot do both. If your character is attacked by many foes, they may make multiple Dodge attempts in a round, but each roll after the first is made at a cumulative \u8211-30% penalty to the skill rating. Some missile attacks are {\i Difficult} or {\i Impossible} to dodge (see {\i Dodging Missile Weapons}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Drive (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 20% or 01% (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use Drive to steer, maneuver, and control a ground vehicle, whether pulled by animals or powered by an engine. For common vehicles, the base chance is 20%, for unknown/uncommon vehicles, it\u8217's 01%. A fumble when driving normally means the vehicle may not start, or a collision or crash. Success means your character gets where they\u8217're going, or is able to correct a bad condition (like a slide or spin), and superior successes mean more distance covered in less time, less fuel used, or some other benefit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Automobile, Bicycle, Carriage, Cart, Chariot, Dogsled, Motorcycle, Truck, Sleigh, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Adjust the base chance by the user\u8217's familiarity where appropriate, but when in doubt, assume that base principles apply.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Most day-to-day driving is an {\i Automatic} task\u8212-a Drive roll is only required under adverse conditions or for extraordinary driving (speeding through a busy downtown area, chasing another vehicle, etc.). To tail another vehicle without being noticed, use an opposed Drive roll vs.\u160 ?the other driver\u8217's Spot. To resolve vehicle chases, see {\b Chases}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Energy Weapon (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon specialty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this to fire any kind of hand-held directed energy or beam weapon (lasers, blasters, disruptors, etc.).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Energy Pistol, Energy Rifle, etc. Specialties are equivalent to types. See {\b Weapon Classes} in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for firearm types.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Missile Weapon Fumble Table} for specific effects. Energy weapons usually impale.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Energy weapons usually only appear in futuristic settings. Anyone from a culture without them must make a {\i Difficult} Idea roll to figure out how to use one, and perhaps only after seeing it used. Failures or fumbles can be disastrous, to the weapon or the user! A military background may be required to learn this skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Some energy weapons have a minimum STR and DEX requirement to use the weapon, as per the weapons tables in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Energy weapons do not use damage modifiers but can be used for aimed attacks. They cannot be dodged, though target movement and orientation can impose penalties to the shot, as described in {\i Dodging Missile Weapons}. Blocking energy shots with the Shield skill is {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Etiquette (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most cultures, castes, or groups have social rules and codes of behavior. Proper dress, modes of speech, specific behaviors, body language, or even trials by combat can all play a part in a group\u8217's etiquette. Use this skill whenever your character needs to behave appropriately, whether attending a Victorian dinner party, an important job interview, or joining an organized crime family. Etiquette rolls might gain an audience with an important nonplayer character or impress others with your knowledge of their social mores. A fumble represents a disastrous faux pas, a fail does not impress, and success or better yields superior results and improves one\u8217's reception.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Specialty: By group. To learn the manners of a second group, learn a second Etiquette skill with that specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The gamemaster should only call for Etiquette rolls in important circumstances: for example, the first time interacting with an important group, a significant occasion, or when trying to advance status within the group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Fast Talk\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The preferred weapon of salesmen, spies, or con artists, use this skill to convince a target quickly of something they may not believe, or convince them to make a rapid decision against their better judgment. Use this to bluff one\u8217's way past a doorman or make a hard sell go quickly. Fast Talk is quick to use, and usually temporary: a few minutes and a successful Idea roll later, and the target may come to their senses. To truly change someone\u8217's mind, use the Bargain or Persuade skills. A fumble usually draws hostility, failing gets you nowhere, and success or better has improved effectiveness, or even convinces someone permanently of your position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Good roleplaying and/or an effective argument might make a Fast Talk attempt {\i Easy}, just as poor roleplaying and/or a flimsy argument might make it {\i Difficult}. Trying to Fast Talk a target after a first attempt at Bargain, Fast Talk, or Persuade fails is {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Fine Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A measure of steadiness and hand-eye coordination, this skill covers any careful use of the hands and fingers. Use it when picking locks, disarming a trap, tying or untying knots, and disassembling mechanical devices. A fumble bungles things, perhaps breaking or jamming the item being manipulated. Superior successes take less time, make it easy in the future, show no signs of tampering, or some other similar benefit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Using this skill without appropriate tools, where required, is {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Firearm (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon specialty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This skill measures accuracy with firearms, and provides familiarity with handling, maintenance, and basic repairs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Machine Gun, Pistol, Revolver, Rifle, Shotgun, Submachine Gun. Specialties are equivalent to types. See {\b Weapon Classes} in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for firearm types.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Missile Weapon Fumbles Table} for specific effects. Firearms usually impale (see {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for details).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Any character unfamiliar with firearms must make a {\i Difficult} Idea roll to figure out how to use one if they have not seen it in use. Failures or fumbles can be disastrous, to the weapon or the user!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Some firearms have a minimum STR and DEX requirement, as per the weapons tables in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Firearms do not use damage modifiers, and can be used for aimed attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 First Aid\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 30%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to stop bleeding, bandage wounds and treat minor burns, set a broken limb, resuscitate someone who\u8217's drowning, or revive an unconscious person. It extends to triage and rudimentary medical care but has little effect on poisons, diseases, or subtle physical ailments: these must be treated with the Medicine skill, though your gamemaster may allow a Difficult roll for emergency treatment of poison or disease. First Aid takes a full combat round and cannot normally be performed while in combat. If interrupted, the attempt must be restarted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} First Aid has specific effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} The patient takes 1 general hit point of damage, and their condition remains unchanged.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} No effect, and no further First Aid attempts may be made.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} One of the following (player choice):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Heal 1D3 hit points to a single wound or injury.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab A character at 0 or negative hit points in this or the previous round, can be restored to life if their hit point total is brought to 1+.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Reviving an unconscious character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Stopping bleeding damage from a bleeding special success or any other ongoing damage to a hit location\line (see {\b Hit Points per Hit Location}).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} As above but healing 2D3 hit points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} As above but healing 3+1D3 hit points.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Keep track of individual injuries, as First Aid can be used on each injury, potentially healing it up to the amount of hit points the injury inflicted. Only one attempt may be made per wound. Hazardous or unsanitary conditions may make rolls {\i Difficult}. Your character may add 1/2 of their Medicine skill rating and 1/5 of their Science (Pharmacy) skill rating as a temporary bonus to First Aid rolls. Modern medical equipment (painkillers, bandages, or medicine) may add up to a +20% bonus to skill ratings, while futuristic medical technology (artificial spray skin, medical scanners, nanotech healers) can make all First Aid rolls {\i Easy}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Fly\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} DEX\u215 ?4 or 1/2 DEX (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For beings with wings, the appropriate gear (antigravity belt, rocket boots, etc.), or flight powers, use this skill to maneuver in the air without a vehicle. Use Fly to perform aerial maneuvers or acrobatics without losing control, outmaneuver a foe in aerial combat, or fly in poor weather conditions. Base chance is DEX\u215 ?4 for winged creatures; 1/2 DEX for all others. For jet packs, hang-gliders, etc. use the Pilot skill. See {\b Aerial Combat} and {\b Chases} for more information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Fly has specific effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} Stall and perhaps even fall. Winged characters must make a successful Stamina roll or suffer 1D3\u8211-1 points of damage from a sprain or strain. A device stalls or fails and cannot keep your character aloft. The flyer falls one round per altitude level above the ground. Make a {\i Difficult} Fly roll to stay aloft\u8212-failing means a crash (see {\b Falling}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} Off course or drops to an undesirable altitude. Goes nowhere.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} Completes the desired maneuver or holds position in a chase\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} Completes the desired maneuver and gains a +10% bonus to the next Dodge, Fly or attack roll made in aerial combat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} Completes the desired maneuver and gains a bonus of +25% to the next Dodge, Fly or attack roll made in aerial combat.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Short, uneventful flights under normal or moderate conditions are {\i Automatic}. See {\b Weather Conditions} for modifiers to flight. Stamina rolls are required for long-range flights, with the characteristic multiplier decreasing by one every four hours or fraction thereof spent in the air. Normal flight does not expend fatigue points, while maneuvering or stressful flight is a strenuous activity. Flying while wearing armor or heavy gear incurs a penalty equal to your character\u8217's current ENC total (see {\b Encumbrance}). A flying character carrying a heavy object must match their STR against the SIZ of the carried object on the resistance table to stay aloft.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Gaming\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} INT+POW%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill while playing games, from chess or backgammon to gambling contests involving cards, dice, or other random or strategic elements. Gamblers make their living using this skill, but to most others it is merely a source of entertainment. A fumble cleans you out and potentially puts you into debt, failure means you lose the round, success yields a minor win, and superior successes reap greater benefits and perhaps even improves one\u8217's status.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Use this to resolve games where skill and strategy play some part, with other players making an opposed roll. To cheat, use Sleight of Hand or Fast Talk, opposed by Observe or Insight. Utterly random outcomes use Luck rolls.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Grapple\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill for wrestling or any fighting where the goal is to subdue a target without causing harm. Usually this is non-lethal, but it can be used to deliver real harm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Grappling has specific effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} Roll on the {\b Natural Weapons Fumble Table}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} The target eludes being held, or an attempted escape fails.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} The target is grappled, attacker can apply one grapple effect (see {\b Grapple Effects} below) next round if the hold is maintained.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} The attacker automatically succeeds in their next Grapple roll to maintain the hold and gains a +3 characteristic bonus on any resistance rolls for grapple effects made this round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} The attacker automatically succeeds in their next Grapple roll to maintain the hold, and the target\u8217's characteristics are halved in any resistance rolls for grapple effects during the remainder of that combat round.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The attacker must make a Grapple successfully to establish a hold on the target. Successful attacks grab a random hit location (if that system is used). Grapples can be parried with the Grapple skill: if the defender parries with a weapon or shield, the attacker automatically grabs the weapon arm or shield arm if the Grapple roll is successful. Once a hold is established, the attacker must make a successful Grapple roll each round to maintain the hold. Taking any action other than one of the grapple effects breaks the hold. Once held, the target can attack their attacker if they have a limb free, using Brawl or any small weapon (knives or handguns). If both hands are free, the target can attempt to Grapple back.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Multiple attackers can attempt to grapple a single target, though no more than two attackers can hold any one location. Combine the STR ratings of both attackers in all contested tests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Grapple Effects\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An attacker with a hold on their target can attempt any of the following effects, one per round, beginning the round after the Grapple takes hold. Some effects can only be used if the attacker has grabbed a specific body part (see below). As some effects involve specific hit locations, the gamemaster may need to interpret results.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Change Hold (Any):} Match DEX vs.\u160 ?DEX on the resistance table. If successful, the attacker shifts hold to a different hit location of choice. If unsuccessful, the target can take an action, though the attacker still has a hold on the original location.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Disarm Target (Arm):} The attacker matches STR+SIZ vs.\u160 ?the target\u8217's STR on the resistance table. If the attacker succeeds, the target drops anything in that hand, and the arm remains immobilized. If unsuccessful, the target hangs on to the held item(s), though their arm remains immobilized. The attacker retains the hold.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Grab a Second Location (Arm/Leg):} The attacker tries to grab and hold another hit location of their choice. Match the attacker\u8217's DEX vs.\u160 ?the target\u8217's DEX+SIZ on the resistance table. If the attacker wins, they grab the second location and keep the already held limb trapped. If unsuccessful, the target immediately matches their STR vs.\u160 ?the attacker\u8217's STR on the resistance table to break all holds. The attacker can hold as many locations as they have hands.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Injure The Target (Head/Chest/Abdomen):} The attacker elbows, gouges, or squeezes, inflicting 1D3 damage plus their damage modifier to the target (general or to the held hit location). The target may immediately match their STR vs.\u160 ?the attacker\u8217's STR on the resistance table to break the hold.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Immobilize Limb (Arm/Leg):} Match the attacker\u8217's STR vs.\u160 ?the target\u8217's STR on the resistance table. If the attacker wins, no action can be taken with that limb until the hold is broken. If unsuccessful, the target can take an action, though the attacker still has a hold on the limb.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Immobilize Target (Head/Chest/Abdomen):} Match the attacker\u8217's STR vs.\u160 ?the target\u8217's STR on the resistance table. If the attacker wins, the target can take no action at all until the hold is broken. If unsuccessful, the target can still take actions, though the attacker still has a hold.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Knockdown Target (Head/Chest/Abdomen):} The attacker automatically overbears the target, dragging both characters prone. The target must make an Agility roll or suffer 1 point of general damage (or to a random hit location).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Strangle Target (Head):} The target must make a CON\u215 ?1% roll each round or suffer 1D3 damage to their general hit points. The target may immediately match their STR vs.\u160 ?the attacker\u8217's character\u8217's STR on the resistance table to break the hold. Once the attacker begins strangling, they do not need to make further Grapple rolls each round to maintain the hold. The target must attempt to break free (see {\b Choking, Drowning, and Asphyxiation}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Throw Target (Special):} Match the attacker\u8217's STR+DEX against the target\u8217's SIZ+DEX on the resistance table. Throwing a target releases any hold. If the attacker is successful, the target is thrown 1D6 meters, is automatically knocked down, and must make an Agility roll or suffer 1D6 general damage (or to a random hit location). A roll of DEX\u215 ?1% allows them to land on their feet without taking damage. If the roll is unsuccessful, the target is not thrown and may take an action, though the attacker retains a hold. A throw may be attempted with any limb held, but a successful roll with the head simply inflicts 1D6 points general damage (or to the head hit location) and does not result in a throw.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Heavy Machine (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to operate any machine larger than a person and any wheeled vehicle heavier than a moving van, such as a forklift, tank, bulldozer, crane, locomotive, or operate the engines on a large seagoing vessel. Heavy Machine also covers basic care and preventative maintenance, though once a heavy machine fails, a Repair skill is required to fix it. For aircraft, use the Pilot skill. A fumble results in a crash, engine troubles, and/or property damage, while failure means the machine doesn\u8217't do the desired task. Successes and superior successes indicate greater effectiveness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} By vehicle type (Armored Vehicles, Boilers, Bulldozers, Cranes, Engines, Turbines, etc.).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Generally, heavy machines are unable to participate in chases, but certain kinds of machines can be used as weapons, doing 3D6 to 6D6 damage, based on the size of the device. Using this skill outside normal performance is {\i Difficult}, as is operation and maintenance in extreme conditions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Heavy Weapon (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon specialty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to operate explosive weapons or large direct-fire weapons that push the limits of portability, such as includes bazookas, rocket launchers, heavy machine guns, tripod-mounted laser cannons, and others. Use the Artillery skill for heavier ordnance such as cannons, siege engines, or vehicle- or pintle-mounted weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Heavy weapons fall between traditional weapons and artillery and are often used to deliver explosives. Specialties are by weapon type, and include Bazooka, Flamethrower, Mini Gun, Rocket Launcher, etc. See {\b Weapon Classes} in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for more details.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Missile Weapon Fumbles Table} for specific effects. Heavy weapons usually impale or knockback.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Most heavy weapons employ automatic fire, or shoot explosive ordinance. See {\b Autofire} and {\b Explosions}. All missed shots go somewhere; the gamemaster should decide where missed explosive shots impact.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Hide\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 10%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The art of concealing an object or oneself from view. Your character should use this skill to escape during pursuit, keep an object from easy detection, or avoid surveillance. A fumble draws immediate attention, failure means that Spot roll to find the hider becomes {\i Easy}, a success requires a Spot roll to be found, and superior successes either make the Spot roll {\i Difficult} or {\i Impossible}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Hide checks are opposed by the Spot of an observer or searcher. Adequate cover is essential; hiding in scant cover is {\i Difficult}, and a total lack of cover (wide open, broad daylight) makes it {\i Impossible}. Special clothing or gear (face paint, camouflaged clothing, etc.) can add a bonus of up to +20%, depending on its quality. Environmental conditions may offer additional bonuses. Someone hiding should keep as still as possible; moving while using Hide {\i Difficult}, and moving more than a meter in a combat round requires both Hide and Stealth rolls. Hide is only effective against visual and aural detection; advanced sensors may find a hiding character by body heat, or a keen nose might find them using the Sense skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Insight\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to evaluate another person\u8217's character, emotional state, and motives based on body language, speech patterns, and other intangible factors. Insight allows a gambler to sense a bluff, or a detective to sniff out a lie. A fumble provides misleading information, failure yields nothing, success lets you know what the target might be thinking, and superior successes reveal to you their innermost thoughts (within reason).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} This skill can be opposed by Etiquette, Fast Talk, or even Persuade. Using this skill on close friends, family members, or spouses is Easy. If using the {\b Personality Traits} system, Insight can determine the strength of those traits in general terms (such as \u8220"Very selfish\u8221", for example).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Jump\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to leap for height or distance, jump over obstacles. Under normal circumstances, a reasonably fit human can jump their height horizontally and half their height vertically from a standing position, and roughly three meters horizontally with a running start. A fumble results in a fall (1D6 general hit point damage or to a hit location), a success results in a jump as described above, a special success increases the amount by 50%, and a critical success doubles it. Jump can also reduce falling damage by 1D6 per level of success (normal success by \u8211-1D6, special by \u8211-2D6, critical by \u8211-3D6).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} A standing jump requires 1 DEX rank. A running jump uses the same DEX rank as normal running movement. Performing flashy or showy jumps (somersaults, flips, etc.) is {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Knowledge (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05% or 00% (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This skill represents experience or academic study of a branch of knowledge. Use a Knowledge skill to remember pertinent facts, to analyze or identify clues, make logical suppositions, and recall impressive trivia. For more scientific ones, see Science. A fumble results in misleading and inaccurate falsehoods, and successes yield more useful and detailed information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Accounting, Anthropology, Archaeology, History, Law, Occult, Religion, etc. (see nearby list) The gamemaster should determine whether the Knowledge skill has a base chance of 05% for specialties that are common, or 00% for those requiring research and study to even have a rudimentary understanding of.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} In fantasy and historical settings, only a small subset of specialties exist. As settings grow more modern, specialties increase.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The optional EDU characteristic and Knowledge roll cover most common knowledge\u8212-specialized information is represented by an appropriate specialty of a Knowledge skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Knowledge Specialties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following list of specialties is by no means comprehensive and should be expanded as needed. Some specialties have subspecialties, specific focuses on a single subject within that field. Write them like this on your character sheet: Knowledge (Group/Templars) or Knowledge (Templars), as desired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Academic Lore (Ancient Eras Only):} In eras when the whole of written knowledge can be contained in a single library, this represents how \u8216'learned\u8217' one is. Use it like a Knowledge roll for nearly any area of knowledge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Accounting:} Use it for analyzing bookkeeping, financial analysis (debt, bankruptcy, wealth, net worth, etc.), and to identify financial irregularities (strange spending, embezzlement, or odd windfalls).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Anthropology:} The study of cultures, including customs, art, and behavior. Use it to identify a person or artifact\u8217's native culture or to determine a culture\u8217's social mores and behaviors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Archaeology:} The study of ancient and vanished cultures. Use it to identify an artifact from a dead culture, spot a fake, or conduct an excavation and make reasonable inferences about the history of a site or region.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Art History:} The study of art from various eras and places, including style, famous artists, and specific works. Use it to identify the origin of a piece of art, spot a fake, or attribute a work to a known master.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Blasphemous Lore:} The study of horrific occult secrets and ancient evils. The more of this knowledge your character has, the less their grasp on sanity. See the optional Sanity rules for more information. Blasphemous Lore skill begins at 0%, not 05%, and cannot be increased with experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Business:} The study of entrepreneurial practices, guild regulations, corporate laws, and management techniques for a commercial enterprise. Use it to identify major players in a field or market, predict economic trends, and turn a profit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Espionage:} Knowledge of spy organizations, famous or notorious spies and agents; methodology, notable figures, organizations, tactics, etc. Use it to know about agencies and their modus operandi. Codebreaking is handled with Science (Cryptography).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Folklore:} Knowledge of the customs, stories, lyrics, tall tales, and legends of a particular people or region. Use this skill to identify or remember elements of a folk tale or fable, whether rustic or supernatural.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group/Subspecialty:} General information about a particular culture, nationality, group, club, or social class. Use this skill to identify a member of that group, know \u8216'who\u8217's who\u8217' within that group, and remember social customs and mores of the group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b History:} The study of past events and eras. Use this skill to remember the significance of any place, person, event, or object, or to correctly guess when an object or document was made.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Law:} The study of legal practice and precedent. Use this skill to judge the legality of a proposed action, find legal precedents, free oneself from trouble with the authorities, or build a case for or against a criminal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Linguistics:} The study of language itself, from the foundations of grammar and vocabulary to how societies shape languages. Use this skill to identify unknown languages or puzzle out a few words or grasp a basic meaning, although this skill is no substitute for the appropriate Language skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Literature: }The study of significant prose, poetry, and essays, usually from a single culture. Use this skill to properly identify a quote or allusion to a specific work, identify when and where an unknown fragment might have been written, attribute a mysterious work to a known author, spot a literary fake, or quote ominously appropriate passages from famous works of literature.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Occult:} Knowledge of magic, obscure legends, and so-called \u8216'secret history\u8217' that covers everything from arcane philosophies to modern conspiracy theories. Use this skill to realize the significance of alchemical or astrological symbols, identify which magical tradition created a ritual workspace, know the names of powerful spirits, or identify the secret factions conspiring to manipulate a situation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Philosophy:} The study of existence and its meaning, from basic logic to existentialism, nihilism, and beyond. Use this skill to remember the precepts of a particular philosophy, identify the philosophical leanings of an author or speaker\u8217's argument, and to engage in philosophical debate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Politics:} The study and knowledge of political systems or other means of governance imposed upon or elected by the citizenry. Use this skill to understand the major power blocs in an area, how to influence the political structure, and how citizens will react to political change or influence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Region/Subspecialty:} General information about a specific city, region, or nation, including important people, local landmarks, and regional history. Use this skill to find cheap lodgings in a bustling city, remember the best roadside inn in the province, understand local politics, or find specific merchants or tradesmen.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Religion/Subspecialty:} Details of the mythos, liturgy, and practices of a specific religion. Use this skill to avoid violating taboos, recall the laws and obligations of a faith, successfully debate points of theology, identify regalia or religious texts, sort orthodoxy from heresy, or properly lead a religious ceremony.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Streetwise:} Knowledge of the shadier segments of a society, from the protocols of the poor to the ways of the criminal underworld. Use this skill to find a safehouse, identify a fence for stolen goods, or know who to ask for other semi-legal or illegal favors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Language (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} INT\u215 ?5 (or EDUx5) or 00% (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The ability to communicate verbally in a language, either one\u8217's native language or another. Other languages can be learned in the home, at school, on the streets, or at school, depending on the culture and upbringing. Most characters begin knowing their own language at INT\u215 ?5. Bilingual characters must have spent skill points on another language skill. Day-to-day conversation in one\u8217's own Language is {\i Automatic} and does not require a skill roll. Skill rolls are only required when communicating difficult concepts or in difficult and unusual situations, such as translating. This skill covers verbal communication\u8212-reading and writing use Literacy. A fumble means disastrous misunderstanding, while successes yield smooth and sometimes eloquent communication.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Per language. Each specialty applies to a single language; if you wish for your character to learn an additional language, they must build up an additional Language skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} If the EDU optional rule is used, choose the higher of INT\u215 ?5 or EDU\u215 ?5 for the base chance. Understanding obscure dialects or ancient varieties of a language is {\i Difficult}. Complex or long documents or conversations with several salient points might require multiple language rolls to understand, one for each point. See the {\b Language Fluency Table} for details about how skill rating impacts communication and fluency.\par}
