{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Listen\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to hear, interpret, and understand sounds, whether murmurs behind a closed door, furtive whispers, stealthy footfalls, and snapped twigs. Use this skill to see if a noise wakes a sleeping character, or to see if they can recognize a specific sound or voice. The normal range for hearing a human voice speaking at a polite volume is 15 meters\u8212-louder voices carry farther, and quieter ones have a shorter range. A fumble means a misunderstanding or complete ignorance of a sound, while successes yield awareness and information about its source.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Listen is both active and passive skill: your character can attempt to Listen for suspicious noises, or the gamemaster can call for Listen rolls when appropriate. Oppose Listen with Stealth to resolve attempts to sneak past a wary or unwary listener. The gamemaster may choose to make Listen rolls secretly and inform you of the result, to avoid giving anything away if the roll fails.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Literacy (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 00% or equal to Language (Own/Other) (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The ability to read and write is taken for granted in the modern era: in previous ages, reading and writing were products of elite education and signs of distinction or status. In modern societies, the base chance for Literacy is equal to a character\u8217's base Language (Own) or (Other) unless otherwise desired. A fumble means a disastrous misunderstanding, failure means meaning is lost, successes yield critical information or nuances, even renown for work produced.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} By language. Each specialty applies to single written language; additional languages are separate Literacy specialties. In modern societies, Literacy is always equal to your Language skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Understanding obscure dialects or ancient varieties of a written language is {\i Difficult}. Complex or long documents (such as books) with multiple salient points might require multiple Literacy rolls, one for each point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Martial Arts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This represents study and mastery of a specific fighting style. Use this skill to make specific moves and strikes that cause maximum damage to the target. Martial Arts is always used in combination with another skill: Brawl, Melee Weapons, Missile Weapons, or Grapple, as appropriate. This skill is not necessary to make those attacks\u8212-it represents a greater level of training that allows greater effectiveness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} By martial arts tradition: boxing, capoeira, escrima, fencing, jeet kune do, karate, kenjutsu, kickboxing, kung fu, kyujutsu, pugilism, savate, etc. The gamemaster may limit the types of combat skills that can be paired with a Martial Arts, such as only allowing Missile Weapons (Bow) with kyujutsu, for example.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Martial Arts is not rolled separately when making an attack. Roll against the primary skill and compare the result to the Martial Arts skill. Results have these effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} Use the appropriate fumble result (see the attack and fumble tables in {\i Chapter 6: Combat}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} If the rolled result is above the Martial Arts skill rating but still equal to or below the combat skill, the attack hits normally. Attacks rolled above the combat skill miss, regardless of the Martial Arts skill rating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} If the rolled result is less than or equal to both Martial Arts and the combat skill, roll for base damage twice and total the result. Your character\u8217's damage modifier is never doubled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} As above. For a special success, the additional base damage roll is added to the effects of the combat skill\u8217's special result, if any.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} As above. If the combat roll is a critical success, the target\u8217's armor protection (natural or worn) is ignored, and the additional base damage roll is added to the effects of the combat skill\u8217's special result, if any.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The Martial Arts skill works in conjunction with one other combat skill, and usually with a narrow range of specialties for that skill. This power can be used in conjunction with the Natural Weaponry mutation and the Unarmed Combat power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If multiple attacks are made in a round, the attacker must allocate the Martial Arts skill accordingly, dividing it as desired between the multiple attacks, or applying it only to a single attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if your character has Brawl 120% and Martial Arts 46%, and is making two attacks at 60% in around, you must choose to divide the Martial Arts skill between these two attacks (23% each, or some combination equaling 46%), or choose to have it apply to only one of the attacks.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Due to its relative power, the gamemaster may rule that the initial skill rating in this skill be limited, that increases to this skill may be limited to training rather than normal experience, that training may be incredibly difficult to obtain, or all three of these conditions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Medicine\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill is used to diagnose and treat serious injuries, treat diseases, counter poisonings, and make general health recommendations, as well as perform surgery and advise long-term care for chronic health conditions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Medicine has specific results:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} The patient takes 1 general hit point (for injuries) while treating injuries, or loses characteristic point (for poisons or illness), and their condition remains unchanged.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} The patient\u8217's condition does not change, and a second attempt can only be performed on the next day.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} Pick one of the following effects (player choice):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Any effect of a successful First Aid roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The patient\u8217's healing rate doubles from 1D3 to 2D3 hit points per week.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Ongoing characteristic or hit point damage from poison or disease is halted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab A poisoned or diseased character is stabilized and recovers 1D3\u8211-1 hit points or characteristic points per week. This result can only be picked once per week of treatment.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} As above, but an injury is healed by 2D3 hit points, or 1D3 characteristic points are recovered.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} As above, but a wound or injury is healed by 1D3+3 hit points, or 1D3+1 characteristic points are recovered.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Each use of Medicine applies to a single malady: once it has been treated and is completely cured, additional successful Medicine rolls have no effect. Other wounds or maladies, however, can be treated. Unsafe or unsanitary conditions may make Medicine rolls {\i Difficult}. Special equipment or medicine may add up to +20% to the skill rating, while futuristic medical technology (artificial spray skin, medical scanners, nanotech healers) make Medicine rolls Easy. Treating common and non-life-threatening ailments is {\i Automatic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Melee Weapon (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to wield a particular type of weapon in hand-to-hand combat, whether attacking or parrying.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Specialties are equivalent to weapon classes. See {\b Weapon Classes} of {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Each specialty applies to weapons from that category of weapon only: but the gamemaster may allow use of a similar weapon class as if {\i Difficult}. If successful, make an experience check. If the experience roll is successful, start a new skill with a specialty at that rating, plus the gained experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Melee Weapon Attack Fumbles Table} and the {\b Melee Weapon Parry Fumbles Table} in {\i Chapter 6: Combat} for specific effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Your character can attempt more than one parry per round, but each roll after the first is made at a cumulative \u8211-30%. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, your character can wield a weapon from a related or similar weapon category, with the roll being {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Missile Weapon (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this to wield any hand-held self-propelled missile weapon such as bows, crossbows, throwing axes, spears, throwing stars, javelins, blowguns, spear guns, or even boomerangs. For grenades, use Throw.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Specialties are equivalent to weapon classes. See {\b Weapon Classes} of {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Each specialty applies to weapons from that category of weapon only: but the gamemaster may allow use of a similar weapon class as if {\i Difficult}. If successful, make an experience check. If the experience roll is successful, start a new skill with a specialty at that rating, plus the gained experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Missile Weapon Fumble Table} for specific effects. Arrows and pointed weapons usually impale. If you wish to know where a missed missile weapon attack goes, see the Throw skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} All missile weapons have a minimum STR and DEX required to use the weapon, as listed in {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Typically, the attacker\u8217's damage modifier is halved for missile weapons, and for entirely self-propelled weapons (blowguns, crossbows, etc.), the damage modifier is not applied. Missile Weapon can be used for aimed attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Navigate\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 10%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to find the way to a destination whether with a compass, sea charts, the stars, or simply using perception, memory, and intuition as a guide. A fumble means one is hopelessly lost and subsequent roll by anyone to become un-lost is {\i Difficult}. Failure means delays and a slowed rate of travel, while successes mean finding one\u8217's way effectively and even making better-than-expected progress.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Attempt a Navigate skill roll every four hours of an ongoing journey. Use of a map or compass may improve the skill ranking by up to +20%. Navigating in a featureless landscape (at sea, in darkness or bad weather, in a desert, or in dense jungle) without instruments or maps is {\i Difficult}. Advanced navigational aids (global position service technology, etc.) or familiarity with the area make Navigate attempts {\i Easy}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Parry\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to use a weapon or shield to parry or block an incoming attack. This skill is covered in detail in {\i Chapter 6: Combat}. Refer to the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} for more information. The gamemaster may rule that a particular attack cannot be parried, such as from a vastly larger attacker (double or more the defender\u8217's SIZ, for example) or when the attacker is using an area or sweep attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Specialties are equivalent to weapon or shield classes. See {\b Weapon Classes} of {\i Chapter 8: Equipment}. Each specialty applies to weapons or shields from that category of weapon only: but the gamemaster may allow use of a similar weapon class as if Difficult. If successful, make an experience check. If the experience roll is successful, start a new skill with a specialty at that rating, plus the gained experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Melee Weapon Parry Fumbles Tables} in {\i Chapter 6: Combat} for specific effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Your character can attempt more than one parry per round, but each roll after the first is made at a cumulative \u8211-30%. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, your character can parry with a weapon or shield from a related or similar category, with the roll being {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Perform (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to perform, whether acting, dancing, playing an instrument, singing, or exhibiting some other forms of artistic expression. A fumble is a humiliation, failure is uninspiring, while successes yield positive attention, cheers, and perhaps critical acclaim and financial rewards. If recorded and distributed, it may continue to inspire and earn far after the original performance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Act, Conduct Orchestra, Dance, Juggle, Orate, Play Instrument (subspeciality), Recite, Ritual, Sing, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Successful use of the Perform (Ritual) skill may augment a magic power or cause it to have additional benefits, at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Persuade\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 15%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to convince someone that a particular idea or belief is right, correct, or otherwise acceptable , regardless of their original opinion (if any) whether through Socratic logic, structured debate, fiery oratory, empathy, or brute intimidation. Listeners may be convinced to take action or grant a request. Like Fast Talk, truth is irrelevant. Unlike Fast Talk, the effects of successful persuasion last indefinitely, until another Persuade roll or dramatic experience shifts the subject\u8217's opinion. A fumble means the subject may become hostile, embracing the opposite of the desired opinion. Failure is unconvincing. Success sways their opinion, and superior successes yield even better results.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Using Persuade across a language barrier (if both speakers have lower than 50% in the language) is {\i Difficult}, as is convincing someone of something that runs counter to their personality or core beliefs. The gamemaster may reward effective arguments or good roleplaying with a bonus of up to +20%. Depending on circumstances, Persuade could take minutes, hours, or even days, and extended efforts may take multiple rolls to complete.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Pilot (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to steer, maneuver, and control a vehicle through the air, on or under the water, or in space. Larger vehicles may require multiple pilots, and a roll should be made every four hours when not in combat, and once per round during combat or when performing vehicular maneuvers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Airplane, Airship, Balloon, Boat, Helicopter, Hovercraft, Jet Aircraft, Jetpack, Starship, Submarine, etc. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, a pilot may pilot a vessel with a similar specialty as if {\i Difficult}. If successful, make an experience check. If the experience roll is successful, start a new skill with a specialty at that rating, plus the gained experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Most day-to-day piloting is {\i Automatic}\u8212-roll only under adverse conditions or for extraordinary situations. A fumble almost inevitably causes an engine to stall or even crash, failing means the destination is not reached in the desired timeframe, success gets where one desires, and superior successes yield more expert piloting and results. See {\b Aerial Combat} and {\b Chases} for more information, and the {\b Chase Trouble Table} for mishaps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Projection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} DEX\u215 ?2%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This optional skill is used by power-using characters to target power-based attacks. It is described in {\i Chapter 4: Powers} and only used in games with appropriate powers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Psychotherapy\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01% or 00% (see below)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to evaluate and treat mental illness or trauma, particularly restoring lost points of Sanity. In practical terms, Psychotherapy can be used to prescribe drugs and medications, which over time can suspend, treat, and even reverse debilitating psychoses or mental illnesses. Medication and intensive questioning can probe the depths of a damaged psyche and bring back hope from terror and despair. See {\b Sanity} for more information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} Psychotherapy has specific effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} One of the following occurs (gamemaster choice):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The patient must make a new Sanity roll, for a loss of 1/1D3 SAN.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab An existing form of insanity becomes more intense, develops some new symptom, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The patient trades one type of insanity for another: a phobia might lessen, but at the cost of an addiction to mood-stabilizing drugs.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} The treatment has no effect. The patient remains the same and does not recover any lost SAN or heal from any trauma.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} The treatment takes hold, with one of the following effects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab After a month of treatment, the patient regains 1D3\u8211-1 SAN. This skill cannot increase the patient\u8217's SAN above POW\u215 ?5 minus any appropriate penalties for knowledge of blasphemous or unspeakable horror. See {\b Maximum Sanity} for details.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab The underlying cause of an insanity is properly diagnosed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Once the source of an insanity has been diagnosed, it can be treated. Separate rolls must be made for each mental illness treated.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} As above, but the SAN gain is 1D3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} As above, but the SAN gain is 1D3+1.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} This skill is primarily for games where Sanity is used. Treatment requires four to five hours of therapy per month per indefinite insanity. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, Psychotherapy may be used to manipulate a personality trait much as if it were a SAN score, shifting it positively or negatively by the same number of points based on the rolled result above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Setting Notes:} Psychiatric counseling is a relatively modern concept. For settings where psychological treatment does not exist, the base chance is 00%.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Repair (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 15%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Equipment and other objects get damaged or stop working. Use Repair to fix them or make slight modifications and adaptations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Electrical, Electronic, Engineering, Hydroelectric, Mechanical, Structural, Quantum, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} A fumble damages the item further and could even hurt the one making the repair attempt (1D3 hit points for either, for example) and makes further repairs {\i Difficult}. Failure accomplishes nothing, success restores 1D3 hit points and the item becomes usable again or returns to working order. Superior successes yield similar benefits, perhaps using the First Aid skill and the gamemaster\u8217's judgement as a guide. A critical may even improve the item in some small way, such as adding to its total hit point, armor points, or adding a slight bonus when it is utilized.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Research\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to locate and identify potential sources of information in a library, archive, or network. Successful rolls yield the desired information from books, documents, articles, databanks, archives, or websites, with superior successes granting additional or more specific information. Despite the wide range of types of resources, the principles are the same. An attempt at this skill takes four hours normally, though electronic methods are much faster. A fumble leads to a disastrous misunderstanding and results in faulty information. Failure wastes time without any solid results or provides the barest minimum of information after twice the normal amount of time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The gamemaster is advised to make a failed Research roll take longer, give slightly misleading or complicated information, raise some sort of alarm or unwanted attention, or some other setback than simply not yielding any results. Failure is rarely enjoyable in games, and for mysteries, inaccessible clues are a dramatic dead-end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Ride (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Physical\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to ride, handle, and care for of a specific kind of living animal. With Ride your character can steer a mount through special maneuvers or rough terrain, coax it to top speed, or to keep control if it rears or stumbles. A fumble causes a loss of control of the mount, perhaps resulting in being thrown to the ground for 1D6 hit points of damage (general or to a random hit location). A successful Jump roll subtracts 1D6 from the damage total, while the mount gallops away at top speed. Failure causes the animal to balk, and successes yield it performing as desired or even exceeding expectations. Superior successes may yield bonuses to combat actions while mounted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} By animal type. See {\i Chapter 11: Creatures} for example mounts. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, a similar type of animal may be ridden as if {\i Difficult}. If successful, make an experience check. If the experience roll is successful, start a new skill with a specialty at that rating, plus the gained experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Resolve races between the same breeds of animals using opposed Ride checks. Combat and Ride skills must be 50%+ to fight normally in mounted combat. If the Ride skill is less than 50%, a Ride check is required every round to keep control of the mount. If the combat skill is less than 50%, all attacks are Difficult. Even if both skills are higher than 50%, use the lower of the two skill ratings for attacks and parries. If the mount falls, collapses, or dies, treat the rider as if they have been thrown. See {\b Mounted Combat} for more information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Science (various)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 01%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Mental\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to know scientific information and principles from a particular field, and to observe phenomena and draw data-based conclusions. Related information includes the history of the science, familiarity with the equipment and methodology, and an awareness of significant figures and schools of thought in that specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Astronomy, Behavioral Science, Biology, Botany, Chemistry (or Alchemy), Cryptography, Genetics, Geology, Mathematics, Meteorology, Natural History, Pharmacology, Physics, Planetology, Psychology, Quantum Mechanics, Xenobiology, Zoology, etc. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, skill with a related specialty may be rolled as if {\i Difficult}, though a successful roll does not yield an experience check or the chance to begin a new skill with that specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Many Science specialties require specialized equipment, measuring instruments, computers, or even a laboratory. Science rolls can take anywhere from 30 minutes to weeks or months, at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion: four hours for an experiment is a good average. Attempting a Science roll without sufficient time or equipment is either {\i Difficult} or {\i Impossible}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Sense\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 10%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The skill primarily governs taste, touch, and smell; but can extend to some of the less commonly known other senses (physical orientation, gravity, pressure and balance, temperature, etc.). Use it to notice or identify a particular type of stimulus that is not sight (Spot) or sound (Listen), such as finding an item in the dark by touch, identifying a mysterious odor or faint taste, feeling a hairline fracture, etc. At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, this might even extend to a \u8220"sixth sense\u8221" or intuition. A fumble is disastrously misleading or reveals complete ignorance of the stimulus, failure is simple failure to notice, and various degrees of success yield more accurate perception.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Like Listen and Spot, Sense is both active and passive: you can request your character to make a Sense roll, or the gamemaster can call for a roll in appropriate situations. Strong or familiar stimuli are {\i Easy} rolls to Sense, while faint or unfamiliar ones is {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Shield\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} As per shield type\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to block incoming attacks with a shield or other appropriate implement. All shield blocks follow the same rules for parrying: see {\b Shields} and {\b Parry} in {\i Chapter 6: Combat}. One can attack with a shield, treating this skill as if it were a Melee Weapon skill. Damage ratings are given for shields in the weapons lists. Shields do crushing special results, can cause knockbacks, and can be used for aimed attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Effects:} See the {\b Attack and Defense Matrix} and the {\b Melee Weapon Parry Fumbles Table}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Shield blocks are parries. A character may make more than one shield roll in a round, but each additional roll incurs a \u8211-30% penalty to the shield or parry skill rating. Large shields can provide cover against missile or even firearms attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Sleight of Hand\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 05%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Manipulation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use his skill to manipulate small objects (dice, cards, coins, wallets, letters, etc.) in a misleading manner or without attracting attention, such as when picking pockets, cheating at cards, or performing stage magic. A fumble is glaringly obvious: whether the item is dropped, or the would-be thief is caught with their hand in the target\u8217's pocket. Failure means nothing is accomplished, and a unsuspecting target succeeding in an Idea roll may realize that they are being duped.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} The skill is opposed by Spot where appropriate. Once an object has been palmed or taken, use Hide to hide it from a concerted search.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Spot\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 25%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Perception\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use this skill to search a room for potentially important details, find a hidden compartment, notice a fleeting detail, recognize a disguised foe, or spot enemies lying in ambush. A fumble is a hugely distracting misperception or mistaken impression, and different degrees of success yield more useful and pertinent information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Spot is both an active and a passive skill: your character can make a Spot roll to actively search or examine, or the gamemaster can call for a Spot roll to see if your character notices a fleeting detail. Hiding or deliberate concealment requires an opposed Spot vs.\u160 ?Hide test to resolve. Spot is also often opposed vs.\u160 ?Disguise or Sleight of Hand. In complete darkness, Spot is {\i Impossible}, and low light or thick fog makes it {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Status\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base Chance:} 15%\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Category:} Communication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Status is a measure of reputation, professional credentials, social class, prosperity, fame, and even personal honor. Use this skill to influence others by throwing weight around, such as convincing a bank to make a cash loan or forgive a debt, intimidating a nonplayer character to grant a favor, convincing a vendor to settle for an I.O.U., or pressuring authorities into keeping a matter quiet. A fumble is a faux pas of the greatest magnitude, causing shame, drawing unwanted attention, and has the absolute reverse of the desired effect. Successes yield the sought-after results or even additional favors and consideration. Status is not wealth, however, and while they are often connected, they are not intrinsically tied to one another.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} Each specialty represents a single social class, profession, social group, or area of influence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b System Notes:} Status only operates within a given area, by specialty, and using it outside the area of influence is {\i Difficult}. Status is not improved with experience, training, or other improvement. The gamemaster should offer Status as a reward for loyal service, daring deeds, or extraordinary merit between scenarios. One point per adventure is reasonable, with extraordinary deeds or achievements increasing the gain to 1D3, 1D4, or possibly even 1D6 points. Similarly, failure, scandals, misdemeanors, and social improprieties can lower Status. Status can be used to impress, but also to serve as a means of determining renown. Your character rolls against another\u8217's Status to identify them, and a nonplayer character may roll against your character\u8217's Status to determine what, if anything, they know about the character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Status Skill, Social Status, & Character Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As described in {\b Creating a Character} and {\b Character Professions}, Status can have a dramatically affect social standing and wealth. Below are three tables that assign a social rank and average wealth based on Status, with a maximum wealth for that Status. As one earns Status, their position and fortune will likely improve. Your gamemaster should revise these tables or create new ones, as desired.\par}
