{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Precognition can be used actively or passively. In either case, your gamemaster rolls for the ability and announces the results (if any) to you. The results are as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} A clear and coherent vision that is completely inaccurate and misleading.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} An incomprehensible or contradictory flash of insight that does little other than provide an uneasy feeling about a situation and the knowledge that the attempt has failed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} A glimpse into the future up to the time step specified, providing a strong impression of what is to come.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} A view of the future in considerable detail, providing an intuitive sense as to how things will transpire. A successful Idea roll provides guidance as to what actions must be done (if any) to bring about or avoid that outcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical:} A crystal-clear vision of the future including the series of events that immediately precede it, with a clear idea of how to prevent or ensure that outcome.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Active Precognition lets the psychic spend as many power points to see as far into the future as they want, then the gamemaster rolls and announces the results, as above. Once the points are spent, the psychic must make a successful Idea roll to interpret the vision, if there is anything vague or confusing about it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With passive Precognition, your gamemaster secretly rolls for the ability, and if successful, provides a glimpse into the future. In this case, the player may not know the dice are being rolled at all. There is no power point cost for passive use of this psychic ability, and your gamemaster may wish to have some aspect of the environment or situation prompt a precognitive glimpse into the future, perhaps as a dramatic or narrative tool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Note:} Precognition inevitably implies predestination and may require considerable effort on behalf of your gamemaster to bring about effectively. Its role is entirely subject to your gamemaster\u8217's preference, and they should carefully consider its use and impact on gameplay before allowing it, perhaps even adding some long- or short-term drawbacks, such as sanity or fatigue point cost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Psychometry\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Range:} Self\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Duration:} Instantaneous\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Point Cost:} 1 power point per SIZ point of object, plus 1 point per time step\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Objects and environments are psychic sponges, absorbing charged emotions and impressions from those who use and inhabit them, or events that transpired involving them. Psychometry allows a psychic to examine an inanimate item or place and sense the absorbed emotions. This power is only for inanimate objects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For objects, make a Psychometry roll and spend the power points equivalent to the SIZ of the item (minimum 1, see {\b Object SIZ Examples}) plus power points equivalent to the last time the item was used (see the {\b Time Step Table} in Precognition, opposite). A successful Idea roll allows identification of the user of an object if it is someone the psychic has met. For someone they have not met but know of (picture, television, etc.), the Idea roll is {\i Difficult}. The psychic sees one instance of its previous use, or more if they are relatively identical. A psychic can also use Psychometry to determine any special activating code or term used for a device, from a combination for a lock to the magic word that allows a magic wand to be used. This can be attempted only once for each item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For an area, choose some subset of that area to gain an impression and use the SIZ guidelines as above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i rather than try to use Psychometry on an entire car (SIZ 60), use it on a car seat (which is human-sized, roughly SIZ 8).}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Failure means the psychic cannot try again on the specific item or place until their skill with Psychometry has increased.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster may use this ability passively, rolling secretly when the psychic handles an object or enters an area of note, and announcing a sudden flash of insight about a place or thing. Passive gamemaster-promoted use of the psychic ability does not cost any power points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Note:} Psychometry is extremely powerful and can potentially derail a mystery, providing information beyond what your gamemaster wishes. Thus, your gamemaster may choose to disallow this psychic ability. Additionally, it is up to your gamemaster\u8217's discretion whether Psychometry will work on a corpse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Pyrokinesis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Range:} POW in meters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Duration:} Instantaneous, or 1 combat round\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Point Cost:} 3 power points per 1D6 damage or 3 SIZ points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pyrokinesis creates intense heat, filling an area with flame, potentially igniting an object, even providing light or warmth. It can be shaped and otherwise manipulated. The area affected is equal to 3 SIZ per 3 power points. Successful use against a living being inflicts 1D6 points of damage per 3 power points used. Additional power points increase damage (6 points = 2D6 damage, etc.) If the target has some protection such as insulating clothing, this may serve as armor against the damage. Damage is instantaneous, though the heat lingers for an additional combat round or longer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pyrokinesis can melt items, matching the power points spent vs.\u160 ?the object\u8217's SIZ in a resistance roll. Any appropriate environmental effects are also applied, where relevant (see {\b Fire and Heat}). Your gamemaster may choose to modify the number of power points required for substances based on their melting points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pyrokinesis can also snuff out flame by draining the oxygen it requires, cancelling a volume of flame SIZ on a point-by-point basis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Sensitivity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Range:} Self\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Duration:} Instantaneous\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Point Cost:} 1 power point\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This psychic awareness allows the psychic to recognize some supernatural or spiritual aspects of an object or area or to detect the presence of supernatural beings or spirits nearby. Negative emotional, spiritual, or supernatural aspects create foreboding and unease, and positive aspects foster a sense of peace and harmony. If the impressions are coming from an object within the psychic\u8217's immediate vicinity (1/3 POW in meters), an Idea roll identifies that object. Sensitivity also informs whether other psychic abilities are being used or have recently been used in the area, or even if someone nearby has recently used psychic abilities in an extreme fashion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster may wish to use the ability passively, rolling secretly and announcing any sudden flash of Sensitivity. In these cases, it costs no power points to use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Note:} Sensitivity can potentially derail mystery-based plots, and your gamemaster may choose to disallow it entirely. In some settings, this may be the sole psychic ability present.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Telekinesis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Range:} POW in meters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Duration:} 1 combat round\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Point Cost:} 1 power point per 3 SIZ each combat round\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The psychic can lift objects and move them with their mind. Every power point spent affects 3 SIZ points. To use the power, determine the SIZ of the object to be moved and divide its SIZ by 3 (round up). If the Telekinesis is successful, the psychic can pick up the object and move it in the air or along the ground at normal MOV speed. The object must stay within range of the psychic. Every point spent above the SIZ extends the range it can be thrown by another 15 meters, or increases the speed to double (triple, etc.) normal MOV. If something has wheels and/or is dragged across level ground, each point affects 6 SIZ. Once an item is held with Telekinesis, the psychic can hold it indefinitely if they spend the power points to keep it aloft. If knocked unconscious or dealt a major wound, the item falls to the ground. If distracted, attacked, or attempting a complex task, make a successful Idea roll to maintain the hold.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If using Telekinesis to pick up an unwilling target, the psychic must defeat them in a POW vs.\u160 ?SIZ resistance roll. No roll is required for a willing target. Telekinesis cannot lift the psychic themselves: to do that, use Levitation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use Telekinesis to hit someone with an object, make a Throw roll once an object is held aloft. Objects thrown at other characters do 1D6 points of damage per 10 points of SIZ, or the object\u8217's normal damage if it is a missile weapon. The damage modifier is based on the psychic\u8217's POW+INT (instead of STR+SIZ) on the {\b Damage Modifier Table}. To catch an item with Telekinesis, make a successful {\i Difficult} Throw or Agility roll (pick) and spend enough power points to handle the item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Additionally, Telekinesis can be used as armor against physical attacks, each point providing 1 point of armor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Telepathy\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Range:} 10\u215 ?POW in kilometers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Duration:} 1 combat round per power point spent\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Point Cost:} 1 power point to activate or 1 power point per 3 POW\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A psychic can read a target\u8217's mind by making a successful Telepathy roll then defeating them in a POW vs.\u160 ?POW resistance roll. If successful, the psychic must then spend 1 power point per 3 points of the target\u8217's POW (divide POW by three, round up). At this point, they have access to the target\u8217's memories and active thoughts through the rest of the combat round until the psychic\u8217's next DEX rank. The resistance roll must be made successfully each round desired. No resistance roll is required with a willing target, and only 1 point is required to use the ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once a telepathic link is made, choose one of the following actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Speak mind-to-mind as equals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Pass along a simple or complex message, even sharing a memory or image of something.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Read surface thoughts and feelings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Implant a false memory or create a sensory impression that lasts until the target succeeds in a {\i Difficult} Idea roll or the end of the ability\u8217's duration.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a psychic might create a false memory of them giving someone a $100 bill or make them think that a playing card is that $100 bill.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Dig for buried memories or suppressed information in the target\u8217's subconscious. A specific memory may take 1D3 combat rounds, and 1D3+3 rounds for a suppressed or traumatic memory. The target will experience this memory anew, as if remembering it vividly.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once Telepathy has been established, continue it by spending 1\u160 ?additional power point each combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The psychic can attempt to affect more than one target at a time. To do so, make each Telepathy roll separately and pay the requisite power points, but also a successful Idea roll to coordinate the multiple simultaneous communications. The actions taken within the minds do not need to be the same.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The psychic can end the connection immediately. Each combat round after the one in which the telepathic link is established, the target can make a new POW vs.\u160 ?POW resistance roll. Success means the telepathic connection ends. With a successful Idea roll, they know that they were in telepathic contact. A special or critical success reveals the identity of the psychic. If the Idea roll fails, the target has no idea they had telepathic contact, only that it was some strange mental phase.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Sorcery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sorcery imposes supernatural effects on the physical world through complex occult formulas, formalized as spells. A character who uses sorcery is a {\b sorcerer}. When a sorcerer says the required words to activate a sorcery spell and spends the required power points, the specific type of magic energy is released and has the desired effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike {\b Magic}, sorcery spells always happen. Rarely is a roll required to activate the spell, and there is no need for any special targeting. Usually, sorcery only fails if the target cannot be overcome with a resistance roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Who Can Use Sorcery?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer\u8217's POW characteristic influences the frequency and potency of the sorcery they can cast. To be able to cast sorcery spells, a sorcerer must have POW 16+. A sorcerer with POW 15 or lower cannot use sorcery, but they can still use enchanted items and other sorcerers can still cast useful spells on them. Often, their power points are a resource for other sorcerers to aid their own spellcasting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Starting Sorcery Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer begins knowing how to inscribe sorcery spells they know into their grimoire, and they know how to ready or dismiss a spell. Additionally, they already possess a grimoire tailored to their tastes. They know spells depending on the following power levels, and all known spells are inscribed in their grimoires:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Normal:} Up to \u189 ? INT (round up) in levels of spells known.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Heroic:} Up to INT in levels of spells known.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Epic:} Up to INT\u215 ?2 in levels of spells known and/or marked in their grimoire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Superhuman:} Up to INT\u215 ?4 in levels of spells known and/or marked in their grimoire.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer can keep up to their INT in spell levels stored in their mind at any time, so any beyond this are in their grimoire, available but not ready.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Power Points and Sorcery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After casting spells, a sorcerer grows tired, having spent their energy into the sorcery, fueling it. Power points are spent to cast sorcery and return naturally. A sorcerer cannot spend more power points than they possess, nor can their power points regenerate above their POW. Power points over POW can be spent but do not regenerate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some powerful spells may require a sorcerer to spend permanent points of POW as well as power points. Other spells require special herbs, potions, words, or other components. Your gamemaster may rule that additional requirements are necessary, or none at all. If a powerful spell demands sacrifice of POW and power points, the sorcerer\u8217's power points regenerate only to the new POW. If a sorcerer\u8217's POW increases, their power points regenerate to the new value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Sorcery Spell Limitations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer\u8217's INT is the limit to the maximum number of spell levels they have immediate access to. Spells are cast from spells in memory. To cast a spell not in memory, dismiss some other spell to make room.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A human can remember levels of individual spells up to or equal to their INT. Bound demons and elementals also count against this limit. Enchanted items are independent of the INT limit, and do not count against this total. At your gamemaster\u8217's discretion, some cultures with an affinity for magic may have additional capacity for spell memorization.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Think of a sorcerer\u8217's mind like a shelf: spells sit on that shelf. A sorcerer\u8217's INT determines how many items they can have on the shelf at one time. To learn new sorcery while at the INT limit, one must dismiss a spell from memory, essentially taking one thing off the shelf to make room for another.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 List all the spells in a sorcerer\u8217's grimoire in the {\b Powers} section on the character sheet and indicate if the spell is \u8216'In Memory\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once a spell is dismissed, it must be reacquired from a grimoire. A grimoire is a collection that contains spells and sorcerous information. Traditionally, a grimoire is a book or series of books, but it can be a scroll (or scrolls), a computer file, a recording, or almost any means of storing information. Work with your gamemaster for more unusual formats. When your sorcerer character learns a new spell, it can automatically be put into their grimoire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer who loses their grimoire can automatically re-record any spells they currently have in memory and may be able to recall other spells the grimoire contained. Once per day, a sorcerer can attempt to roll INT\u215 ?l or lower. Success means that the sorcerer recalls one spell, or some other bit of lore that was in the lost grimoire (your choice). Failure means no useful information is recalled at that time, and another attempt must wait until the next day.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 When Can Sorcery Be Used?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Spells usually take one combat round to cast. Sorcery in memory is available for use in the Powers phase of the combat round. Sorcery that is not in memory can be readied through different means but is generally not usable during physical combat.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Learning Sorcery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sorcerers learn spells in one of four ways: scholarly research, studying a grimoire, being taught, or accepting the gift of sorcery from a powerful supernatural force.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Scholarly Research\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This option requires a library in a language (or languages) the sorcerer can read. Your gamemaster should determine the {\b library rating}, a multiplier from \u215 ?1\u8211-3; the higher, the better the sources. They then determine the language(s) of the library\u8217's resources. A sorcerer then attempts to either find a new spell or recreate one that may exist somewhere in the library.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster rolls 1D10 secretly to determine the number of weeks needed to attempt to learn the spell, subtracting \u8211-1 week for each 50% in relevant language(s) the sorcerer knows to a minimum of 1 week. When the required time has passed, roll D100: success is equal to or less than the sorcerer\u8217's INT multiplied by the library\u8217's rating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the roll is successful, the spell is learned and inscribed in the sorcerer\u8217's personal grimoire. A failed roll means that the sorcerer must spend another 1D10 weeks (modified as above) before they can attempt another INT\u215 ?(library rating) roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the goal is an invocation or summoning of a particular deity, a temple to that deity is likely to contain the proper information. Research in a temple is the same as in a library, but access may be even more restricted. Your gamemaster should determine what access a sorcerer may have, and such a request may involve some form of service to the temple.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Studying a Grimoire\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A grimoire is a collection of spells, lore, formulas, and rituals. Though these rules refer to a grimoire as a type of book, a grimoire might be a scroll, a staff carved with runes, or some other sort of record, perhaps protected with a code, written in a secret language, or obscured through some other means.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Every sorcerer automatically owns a grimoire inscribed with the spell(s) they know. Traditionally, the grimoire is automatically updated whenever a new spell or other information is learned. No roll is required to do so, and it is assumed to always be successful.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Grimoires allow a character to know more sorcery than their INT allows, ensuring that sorcery is available even when it is not in memory. Grimoires have no maximum or minimum size. Nothing limits a grimoire\u8217's capacity. A sorcerer can start a new or duplicate grimoire at any time. An empty grimoire is just a book with blank pages, ready to be filled with sorcery spells. The only expense is the cost of the actual physical object of the grimoire\u8212-the fancier, the more expensive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Grimoires can be written in a variety of languages, including magical languages. Your gamemaster should determine the language of any other grimoire if one is introduced. A sorcerer must be able to read the writing to learn from the grimoire. A sorcerer with a skill rating of less than INT\u215 ?5 in the language the grimoire is written in must make a successful Language roll whenever the grimoire is used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Other grimoires can come into a sorcerer\u8217's possession through several ways and are often prized possessions. A grimoire for sale may be a musty tome that has survived the death of its owner, or it may be a bundle of cheap spiral notebooks scrawled with tiny handwriting and disturbing pictures. Or it could even be a meticulously organized data file, complete with audio files to assist in pronouncing the difficult passages of the spell, copiously annotated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The spells and summonings in a grimoire may be set down incompletely or deliberately incorrect and may include subtle traps to guard against thieves. References, measurements, and wordings of the spell description are likely to be allusive and baffling. Learning from an old grimoire is often tedious and difficult: the older the grimoire, the more involved the process is likely to be.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To learn a spell from another person\u8217's grimoire, a sorcerer can attempt a roll of equal to or lower than their INT\u215 ?l for every three game weeks of study. With a successful roll, the spell is in memory and ready to be cast (and has been transferred to the sorcerer\u8217's own grimoire).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Being Taught\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Learning a spell from a teacher may be quicker than creating it or deciphering it from a grimoire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The teacher must know the spell and be able to cast it successfully.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A sorcerer can learn one spell at a time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The student must attempt a roll of their INT\u215 ?1. Success means that the spell is in memory and ready to cast. The spell can then be transcribed to the student\u8217's grimoire.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Accepting Sorcery as a Gift\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A powerful supernatural entity like a god, angel, demon, etc. may grant the ability to use a spell through one of the following methods:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The supernatural being might simply place the spell into the sorcerer\u8217's memory (eliminating another spell to make room, if necessary), as if the sorcerer had learned the spell. They can then write the spell down in their grimoire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The spell might be on a scroll, in a book, a shard of some precious metal, a data file, or a banner bearing the words of the spell. It can be learned if it can be read.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The spell may be imbued into an enchanted object of some sort.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The spell may not even be taught to the sorcerer, but instead, they can call upon the supernatural entity and ask it to cast the spell on their behalf.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A gift of sorcery may come with strings attached, known or unknown, and should be accepted cautiously.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Readying and Dismissing Sorcery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As noted previously, a sorcerer cannot automatically cast any spell they know\u8212-spells must be in memory before being cast. You should note on your character\u8217's sheet what spells are in memory and which spells are in their grimoire, perhaps keeping these lists separate from each other to prevent confusion. The {\i Basic Roleplaying} character sheet has adequate space for powers, so the front is the best place for \u8216'ready\u8217' spells, and the back can serve as the grimoire. Alternately, cards or another method can be used to keep them distinct.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To ready a spell, the grimoire should be available, and the relevant spell must exist in that grimoire. Bringing a spell into memory is called readying a spell. Removing a spell from memory is called dismissing a spell. This is done as often as desired: sorcerers often choose their spells based their immediate plans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a sorcerer planning to cast some major spell (like a demon summoning) would ready spells like Brazier of Power, Chain of Being, Refutation, Bolster the Soul, and Witch Sight, along with the Summon Demon spell. If out adventuring, other spells such as Inescapable Bonds, Cloak of Night, Heal, Muddle, Sorcerous Armor, Undo Sorcery, and a weapon enhancement may be more appropriate.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reading and comprehending a spell in the grimoire takes one combat round for each point of the spell to be readied. For spells that vary in points, the number of combat rounds needed always equals the maximum value known.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i it takes four combat rounds to read Hammer of the Gods (4) from the grimoire and have it ready to cast.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a spell requires 20 power points to cast, then a sorcerer needs 20 combat rounds to ready it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Dismissing a spell is much easier. It is instantaneous and can be done at the same time as readying another spell. A demon or elemental can also be dismissed just as quickly, releasing it from service and allowing it to control its own fate. How the creature reacts is up to its nature, the way it was treated, and the relative balance of power between it and its former master.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Spells in Play\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a single number or fixed cost is given for a sorcery spell, the effect always costs that many power points. If the power point cost varies, select the strength of the spell by choosing a number from the given range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unless noted, spells successfully cast take effect automatically (see {\b Other Planes} for exceptions). Once a sorcery spell is cast, it cannot be recalled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some spells are not necessarily detectable by observers, while others are obviously the product of sorcery. A sorcerer will always recognize the effects of a spell they know when it is cast, regardless of who is casting it and what cosmetic elements it has been described with.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Generally, demons, elementals, and other supernatural creatures cannot use sorcery, though sorcery affects them. Demons have their own special abilities that only they possess.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If numerous spells are being cast during an encounter, you might want to use a piece of scratch paper to note spell names, the rounds cast, and spell strengths. Remember to mark off the power points that power the spells.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Casting a Spell\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A spell affects a single person, entity, area, or thing. Since casting takes only one combat round, separate uses of the same spell can strike additional target(s) in later combat rounds.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Spells are cast on the powers phase of a combat round, in order of a sorcerer\u8217's INT. The spell takes effect in INT order of the Powers phase of the next combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After a sorcerer begins casting a spell, they can do nothing else during that combat round. In case of a distraction (being attacked, taking damage, a loud noise or surprise, significant movement, etc.) make an Idea roll to resist being distracted. If the roll is successful, the spell is cast without incident. If the roll fails, the spell is not cast, and the power points are lost. Extreme distractions might make the Idea roll {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Duration\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A spell\u8217's duration equals the sorcerer\u8217's POW in combat rounds.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a sorcerer with POW 19 casts Hell\u8217's Razor. The spell takes one round to cast, then takes effect in the Powers phase of the next round. It lasts for 18 more combat rounds and expires in the Powers phase of the 20th round.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once cast, a spell needs no maintenance, and continues in effect whether the target moves out of range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A sorcerer can extend the duration of any spell by casting it again at any time: the duration extends, but the effect does not intensify. They can choose to end the effects of a spell prematurely: most spells allow this automatically, but others might take more than an instant to cancel. Unless specified otherwise, any ongoing effects of the spell end the moment the sorcerer chooses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 How to Become a Better Sorcerer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 How does a sorcerer become more powerful? Here are three ways to increase POW:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Exercising Power:} A sorcerer that has successfully defeated an opponent of equal or greater POW in a POW vs.\u160 ?POW resistance roll can check the box next to the POW on their character sheet. When checking for experience, see {\b POW Increases}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sorcerous Heritage:} At your gamemaster\u8217's discretion, when creating a sorcerer, trade 2 points from other characteristics for 1 point of POW, deliberately sacrificing aspects of themselves in exchange for greater prowess with sorcery. Each trade requires a successful Luck roll based on their original POW. Missing a Luck roll ends the chance of any further trades. A result of 00 is always a miss. This method is not compatible with point-based characteristic generation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gift of the Gods:} During play, a sorcerer may bargain for or plead for a gift of POW from a favorable deity. This is entirely up to the gamemaster and may require promises of service from the sorcerer, good roleplaying, or successful Communication rolls. The grant is never more than 1D3 POW. For each point granted, the recipient must immediately undertake some dangerous task or attempt some dangerous deed that furthers the deity\u8217's agenda.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Reliability of Sorcery\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some guidelines about how sorcery works:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Spells and sorcerous items do not generally require rolls to activate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Some additional roll may be required\u8212-such as Language to read a spell, or a weapon attack to strike a person with a magic item\u8212-but the sorcerer does not need to make a roll to make the spell itself happen.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Spells take effect automatically, though some require resistance rolls or some other condition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A sorcerous item works for whomever holds it, so long as they have the capability to do so (STR, DEX, etc.).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Sorcery Spell Summary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Following are the sorcery spells from this section, categorized by types, with the range of spell levels in parentheses. Each spell costs 1 power point per level, and each spell\u8217's effect lasts for the duration of the spell (usually a sorcerer\u8217's POW in combat rounds).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Augmentation Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Cloak of Night (1\u8211-4):} Adds +20% per level to Hide.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Leap (1\u8211-4):} Adds +20% per level to Jump.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sureness (1\u8211-4):} Adds +20% per level to Stealth.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Characteristic Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bolster the Soul (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to POW.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Inhuman Plasticity (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to SIZ.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lightning Speed (1\u8211-3):} Adds 1 point per level to MOV.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Relentless Vitality (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to CON.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Suppleness of the Serpent (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to DEX.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Titan\u8217's Strength (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to STR.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Unearthly Beauty (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to CHA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Wisdom of the Sage (1\u8211-3):} Adds 3 points per level to INT.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Combat Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hammer of the Gods (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point damage per level to blunt weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hell\u8217's Razor (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point damage per level to cutting weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sorcery\u8217's Sharp Flame (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point damage per level to impaling weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sorcerous Armor (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point of armor per level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Talons of the Beast (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point damage per level to unarmed or brawling weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Unbreakable Bulwark (1\u8211-4):} Adds 1 point of armor per level to shields.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Enhancement Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Make Fast (1):} Glues together two inanimate objects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Make Whole (3):} Repairs a broken item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Midnight (1):} Creates an area of darkness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Moonrise (1):} Creates a floating globe of light.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Elemental Spells\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bounty of the Sea (4):} Fills an area with water.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fires of the Sun (4):} Fills an area with flame.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gift of the Earth (4):} Fills an area with dirt.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Wings of the Sky (4):} Fills an area with wind.\par}
