{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Skill Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most actions your character attempts are resolved with skill rolls. Here, the percentile roll uses your character\u8217's rating in the appropriate skill as the chance of success. Any skill which normally has a base chance of 5% or higher always succeeds on a roll of 01\u8211-05 chance of success, even if difficulty, conditional modifiers, or other factors reduce the skill rating below 5%. See {\b Modifying Action Rolls}. See {\i Chapter 3: Skills} for more information about each skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Characteristic Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some actions are not easily linked to a specific skill: pulling oneself up a rope, for example. For these situations, use a characteristic roll, with a chance of your character\u8217's characteristic multiplied by a number. CON, INT, DEX, and CHA are common characteristics to use, and most characteristic rolls have a \u215 ?5 multiplier. Your base characteristic rolls were defined in character creation. Depending on the difficulty of the action, your gamemaster may use a higher or lower multiplier. See {\b Difficulty Modifiers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Resistance Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some actions require more than skill or natural ability: obstacles must be overcome to succeed. In these cases, gamemasters should refer to the resistance table and call for a resistance roll. Resistance rolls never involve skills, instead pitting characteristics or other measurable quantities against each other. See {\b Opposed Skill Rolls} for ways to handle skill vs.\u160 ?skill contests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To make a resistance roll, compare the active factor to the passive factor on the resistance table. The active factor is the party or force trying to influence the passive factor. The following are all examples of resistance rolls:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Potency 17 venom (active) poisons your character with a CON 15 (passive). The venom is trying to inflict damage on your character, so the venom is active.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your character has STR 18 (active) and tries to move a SIZ 25 (passive) boulder. Your character is trying to move the boulder, so their STR is active.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The base chance of a resistance roll equals 50% + (active characteristic \u215 ? 5) \u8211- (passive characteristic \u215 ? 5). If the active and passive factors are equal, the active factor has a 50% chance of success. Every point the active factor exceeds the passive factor by modifies the chance of success by +5%, while passive factors higher than active factors modify the base chance by \u8211-5% for every point of difference. Differences of 10 points or more result in automatic success or failure, though your gamemaster may allow a roll of 01 or 00 to succeed or fail, respectively, where results would otherwise be automatic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some specific uses of the resistance table include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Power Points vs.\u160 ?Power Points:} Powers that attempt to influence or control a target often involve contests of power points: your character\u8217's current power point total must overcome the target\u8217's current power points for the power to take effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Potency vs.\u160 ?CON:} All diseases and poisons are measured in terms of Potency (POT) and match this rating against the target\u8217's CON to determine the effects. Depending on the venom or illness, even a failed roll can impair the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b POW vs.\u160 ?POW:} A classic contest of willpower. In addition to winning the resistance roll, success in a POW vs.\u160 ?POW contest gives the active character an opportunity to raise their POW score if they win vs.\u160 ?a higher POW opponent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b STR vs.\u160 ?STR:} Used in arm wrestling, as well as attempts to force open a stuck door or bend an iron bar. These contests involve inflexible obstacles, not heavy ones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Damage vs.\u160 ?CON}: Knockout attacks and blows to the head match the rolled damage against the CON of the target to determine if the target is stunned or knocked out.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b STR+SIZ vs.\u160 ?STR+SIZ:} Overbearing attacks attempt to use the mass and strength of the attacker to knock down the target.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster may wish to always allow for a chance of failure when a result of 00 is rolled, regardless of skill rating. Similarly, a 01 may be a success, even if improbable, though this should be within your character\u8217's capabilities.\par}
