{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Levels of Success and Failure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As with skills, in combat it is often essential to know not only whether an attack or parry succeeded or failed, but also how well it succeeded or how badly it failed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Critical Success\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The best possible roll! A D100 result equal to 1/20 of your character\u8217's skill rating. A critical attack means that the weapon does the maximum possible damage for the weapon used (6 for 1D6, 9 for 1D8+1, etc.) plus the normal rolled damage modifier. Unless countered with a critical parry, a critical attack result always ignores armor, even if that armor is all-encompassing. A critical parry can damage the attacking weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if your character has a weapon skill rating of 60%, they achieve a critical success on a roll of 01\u8211-03. When this is rolled, your character simply takes the maximum damage the weapon can inflict, rolls the damage modifier as normal, and ignores any armor the target may be wearing, whether natural or powered. If the critical success is with a shortsword that does 1D6+1 damage, and your character\u8217's damage modifier is 1D4, the critical damage is 7+1D4 (6+1=7), ignoring the target\u8217's armor. If the weapon is a pistol that does 1D10 damage, the damage is 10 and ignores the target\u8217's armor.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemasters can allow your character to inflict a special success (below) upon a target in place of a critical success, if desired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Special Success\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An exceptional roll. A D100 result equal to 1/5 of your character\u8217's skill rating. Often, a special attack means that the weapon does normal damage in addition to a special result based on the weapon\u8217's type.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i For example, a bludgeoning weapon, like a club, has a knockback/down effect.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A special parry can do damage to an attacking weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i with Firearm 60%, your character achieves a special success on a roll of 04\u8211-12. This does normal damage (1D8, for example), but in the case of a firearm, also does impaling damage.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Success\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A good roll. This is a D100 result equal to or less than your character\u8217's skill rating but higher than the result needed for a special or critical success. Attacks are successful if not parried or dodged, and damage is rolled normally, with no damage done to either attacking or parrying weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i with a skill of Firearm 60%, your character achieves a normal success on a roll of 13\u8211-60. For a firearm that deals 1D8 points of damage, the normal damage is rolled.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Failure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A poor roll. A D100 result greater than your character\u8217's skill rating but less than the highest 1/20 of chance of failure (see Fumble, below). Failing a combat roll means that the attempt failed, but your character can try again later in the same or a following combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i with a Firearm skill of 60%, your character fails on a roll of 61\u8211-97. No damage is rolled, and your target does not need to attempt to dodge or parry the attack.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Fumble\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A disastrous roll! A result of the highest 1/20 of the chance of failure, usually ranging from 96\u8211-100 for lower skill levels to a roll of 100 when character skill levels are over 100%. Often, a fumble indicates a dramatic mishap of some sort, and often forces a roll on the relevant fumble table. See the {\b Melee Weapon Attacks}, {\b Melee Weapon Parries}, {\b Missile Weapon Attacks}, and {\b Natural Attacks and Parries Fumbles Tables}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i with a Firearm skill of 60%, your character fumbles on a roll of 98\u8211-00. No damage is rolled, though you must roll on the {\b Missile Weapons Fumble Table} to determine the result of this botched attack.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some weapons have their chance to malfunction (jam, lock up, etc.), expressed as a high result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a musket always malfunctions on a roll of 95\u8211-00, regardless of the user\u8217's skill.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on the result of the same unfortunate roll and depending on your character\u8217's skill rating, it is possible for your character to both fumble and have a weapon malfunction; to have a weapon malfunction without fumbling; or to have a fumble without a weapon malfunction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i your character has a skill of 60% with a musket and rolls 99 while firing it. Because the weapon malfunctions on a roll of 95\u8211-00, and your character normally fumbles on a roll of 98\u8211-00, this attack is unfortunately both a fumble and a weapons malfunction. If the roll had been a 95, 96, or 97, it would have only been a weapons malfunction.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the result of a fumble specifies an attack on a target other than the intended one, and a malfunction causes a jam, the attack happens before the malfunction (see {\b Malfunctions}).\par}
