{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Acid\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Exposure to acid or corrosive substances can be a hazard. Treat all acids the same: the degree of acid damage represents how diluted it is, rather than the specific type of acid. Only significant contact (the immersion of a limb or contact with the eyes) should cause serious immediate damage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Weak acids inflict 1D3\u8211-1 points of damage per round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Strong acids inflict 1D4 points of damage per round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Very strong acids inflict 1D6+1 points of damage per round.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Armor does not neutralize acid but does momentarily slow its effects. If a target is armored, halve the acid\u8217's damage (round up), though the gamemaster should adjust based on the armor\u8217's type, quality, and coverage. Armor protection against acids lasts 1D3 rounds. After that, the acid inflicts normal damage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Exposure to very strong acid eats away at armor bindings and weakens armor: after 1D6 rounds of exposure, the armor has been functionally destroyed and is useless. This occurs simultaneously with the 1D3 rounds of armor protection\u8212-the armor may have been rendered useless in combat but still offer temporary protection from the acid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster may rule that holy water (or an equivalent) acts as acid against unholy creatures such as vampires or demonic entities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Aerial Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Fly skill covers flight in considerable detail. If your character does not have to use both hands for flight and/or adjust mechanisms (jet-pack controls, for example), they can make attacks while flying. As with riding, your character\u8217's attack and other combat skills are limited by their Fly skill: combat skill ratings are reduced to the level of your character\u8217's Flight skill; if they are lower, the skill remains unaffected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character can make a successful Fly roll during the powers phase of a combat turn (this does not cost an action), any attacks, parries, and other combat actions are unimpaired. The following modifiers may affect your character\u8217's ability to use the Fly skill. See also {\b Weather Conditions} concerning rain, hail, sleet, and snow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Simple Stunt (such as a barrel roll):} No penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Moderately Difficult Stunt (roll):} \u8211-10% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Difficult Stunt (wingover):} \u8211-25% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Extremely Difficult Stunt (loop-the-loop):} \u8211-50% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Light or Moderate Wind:} No penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Strong Wind:} \u8211-10% penalty (no penalty for strong tail wind)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Severe Wind:} \u8211-25% penalty (\u8211-10% penalty for severe tail wind)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Windstorm:} \u8211-50% penalty (\u8211-25% for tail wind)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Hurricane-force Wind:} \u8211-75% penalty (\u8211-50% penalty for tail wind)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Tornado-force Wind:} \u8211-100% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b High Altitude / Low Pressure / Becalmed:} \u8211-25% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Wearing Light Armor:} \u8211-10% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Wearing Medium Armor:} \u8211-25% penalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Wearing Heavy Armor:} \u8211-50% penalty\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All modifiers are cumulative.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a failed Flight roll, any actions a flying character makes are {\i Difficult}. A critical success for the Fly roll makes any rolls made during that round of combat {\i Easy}. If the Fly roll fumbles, your character cannot attack or act in that round and may even fall or crash.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the flight is provided by a vehicle or a flying creature, your character does not have to make Fly rolls\u8212-the skill required is Ride or Pilot, or the Fly skill of the being doing the flying, if applicable. Regardless, the effects of the outcome of the skill roll are applied equally to the rider(s) and the flier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Aimed Attacks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways your character can improve their chance to make a particular shot: to take more time and aim, or to target a specific area. Both can be used for a single shot. If your character is interrupted (attacked, jostled, etc.) while using either method, they must make a successful Idea roll to maintain the aim. If the roll fails, the benefits are lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Taking More Time\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character can take time aiming a missile weapon in return for an increased skill rating. For every five DEX ranks your character delays, add 1/10 of the existing skill rating (round up) as a bonus, cumulative, for the first shot. The missile attack must be made in the same combat round if it is a hand-propelled weapon (bow, throwing knife, etc.), or can be held indefinitely if it is a self-propelled weapon (firearm, energy weapon, etc.). Once the shot is taken, the bonus no longer applies. Careful aim has no effect at ranges beyond double the weapon\u8217's base range. If aiming at a doorway or small aperture and waiting a target to appear in it, the target must be half or less of base range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Targeting a Specific Area\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Targeting a specific part of a victim\u8217's body is {\i Difficult}, though delaying for 5 DEX ranks (as in {\b Taking More Time} above) can offset this modifier. Apply the difficulty modifier before adjusting for taking more time. The gamemaster should determine the result of any successful attacks against targeted areas, such as a {\i Difficult} characteristic roll to maintain a hold on weapon, keep standing, etc. The hit location system (page 126) may be of use for this. If your character targets an unarmored area and is successful, the target\u8217's armor is ignored, just as if a critical hit were rolled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Ambushes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the event of a surprise attack, the attackers gain the advantage of attacks that cannot be countered. For an ambush to be successful, the attacker must make a successful Stealth skill roll, opposed by the intended target\u8217's Listen, Sense, or Spot skill, whichever is appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the attackers are using missile weapons and are not seen, the attackers get a free round of {\i Easy} attacks. The target(s) cannot dodge or parry this initial round of attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the attackers are using missile weapons and are seen, the attackers get a free round of {\i Easy} attacks, but the targets can dodge or parry this initial round of attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the attackers are using hand-to-hand weapons and have not made successful Stealth rolls, the targets must make a successful {\i Easy} Listen, Sense, or Spot roll to notice the oncoming attackers. If the targets fail to detect the attackers, attacks against them are {\i Easy} and any parries or dodges they make are {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the attackers are using hand-to-hand weapons, and the target is aware of them with a successful Listen, Sense, or Spot roll, the attackers\u8217' skill ratings are unmodified and the targets can parry or Dodge normally but cannot retaliate or move until the next combat round.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In most cases, the target\u8217's armor defends normally, unless the attackers are using aimed attacks (above) to bypass armor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After the initial round of surprise, the ambush becomes a normal combat round for all parties involved, with no modifiers due to surprise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Area Attacks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When an attack is aimed at an area with the intent of doing damage to anyone within that area, ranging from divine wrath to grenades, characters in that area can attempt Dodge rolls to avoid damage altogether, or an Agility roll to reduce damage by half (player choice) by getting behind cover. In either case, it is assumed that those formerly in the area have thrown themselves prone to prevent injury (see {\b Prone}). Standing up from a prone position takes 5 DEX ranks. If the area attack is not avoided, it automatically strikes everyone in its area of effect. Depending on the type of attack, this may cause knockback or even being set afire (see {\b Fire and Heat}). At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, shelter or cover may further reduce this damage. Armor should work against damage from area attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Armor Damaged\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Acid, fire, or other corrosive or highly caustic attacks can damage or even destroy armor. It is possible also that a piece of armor can be destroyed by critical hits or even fumbles, though this is at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion. If armor is damaged or loses pieces, reduce its armor value by 1/2, rounding down.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i armor worth 5 points of protection is downgraded to only having 2 points of armor value. If random armor value is used, armor worth 1D8+1 may be reduced to 1D4 protection, which is 1/2 of 1D8, with the +1 rounded down.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Already-damaged armor that is damaged again before being repaired is destroyed, offering no protection but full ENC and burden.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Repairing armor costs half-again the armor\u8217's normal cost. This may be adjusted based on circumstances, such as your character\u8217's relationship with the craftsman, the availability of materials needed for repairs, and the nature of the damage. Armor that has been wholly destroyed can be repaired at the full cost of the armor, but will have 1 point less armor value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Aura Attacks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character may attempt an aura attack, commanding attention with a display of outstanding presence and strength of will. Aura attacks can also be used as an invaluable resource in epic or superhero games. To make an aura attack, your character must average their SIZ, POW, and CHA (round up) into a value called an {\b aura total}. Aura attacks must have a full combat round to initiate if in combat, or they must have at least 12 seconds of preparation if not in combat. An aura attack occurs in the powers phase of the combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When an aura attack is performed, anyone who can view your character must make a resistance roll with their POW characteristic vs.\u160 ?the aura total of your character. Some or all of the following factors may modify the resistance roll:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Command:} Your character may attempt to make a Command roll before making an aura attack. If successful, add +1 to the aura total, a special success +2, and a critical success +3. A fumbled roll reduces the aura total by half (round up).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Previous Success:} If your character has previously succeeded in an aura attack against a target, add +1 to the aura total. A lucky or powerful character can make continued aura attacks against an opponent to keep them at bay, or to paralyze them with fear.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Experience:} At the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, relative fame, a past history with the target, or a successful Reputation roll may add +1\u8211-3 to the aura total.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Passions: A successful appropriate Passion roll can add +1 to the aura total, a special success +2, and a critical success +3. A fumbled roll reduces the aura total by half (round up).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Circumstances:} The situation can also modify your character\u8217's aura total positively, or the target\u8217's POW negatively by \u177 ?1\u8211-3. Reasons might be the display of a powerful magic item with legendary qualities, overwhelming inferiority or superiority in firepower, death of allied combatants, prior defeat or wounded state, or any implied threat accompanying the aura attack.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the resistance roll fails, the target(s) of the aura attack are mesmerized for the remainder of the combat round. They can dodge, parry, or otherwise react to attacks against them, but cannot initiate any attack or other actions of their own volition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This mesmerization ends at the end of the combat round. If the resistance roll is a fumble, the target is demoralized and may surrender, or flee, as appropriate. All actions become {\i Difficult} for a demoralized target for the remainder of that combat round. Whether the result is a failure or fumble, all results end on the last DEX rank of the combat round the aura attack was made.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Aura attacks do not usually inflict horror or cause sanity loss, though your gamemaster may allow certain horrific entities to do so.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Autofire\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many weapons, such as machine and submachine guns, can fire short bursts (multiple shots) or automatic fire (abbreviated as autofire), consisting of a large number of shots as long as the trigger is held down. Autofire or bursts occur on the attacker\u8217's DEX rank.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Against a single target, a burst increases the chance of success by +20% and autofire by +40%. The attacker should announce how many shots are being fired (bursts are usually three shots, while autofire can empty the whole clip), keeping track of spent ammunition. The attack is rolled normally.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the shot is a failure, all shots in the burst miss. If it is successful and hits the target, roll an appropriate die based on the number of shots fired. To get an odd number, roll an appropriate dice type and divide by two (round up). {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if 8 shots are fired, roll a D8; if 5 shots are fired, roll a D10 and divide it in half, rounding up, etc.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The gamemaster may require that all bursts or autofire occur in numbers with dice equivalents, such as 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10, etc. The result of this die roll is the number of shots that hit the target. Only the first attack is able to achieve a special or critical success\u8212-all of the rest are normal successes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For multiple targets, if they are spread across the field of fire, the skill rating does not improve. Instead, each attack uses an unmodified attack roll for each target. The attacker can allocate the number of bullets per target. In this case, each target could potentially receive a special or critical success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If multiple targets are restricted to a narrow field of fire, such as in a corridor or grouped closely together, the attacker\u8217's skill rating is increased by an additional +20%.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Backstabs and Helpless Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If in the midst of hand-to-hand combat, your character can attack the unprotected back of a target, that one attack is {\i Easy}. If the target succeeds in a {\i Difficult} Listen or Sense roll, they can make a {\i Difficult} Dodge or parry attempt, but only if they have any remaining opportunities for defense. No additional damage is done by such an attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, if a target is helpless (unable to move, dodge, or parry), the attack is {\i Easy} and they cannot make a dodge or parry attempt against the attack. Conditions by which a target might be helpless are when they are unconscious, asleep, or restrained entirely.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In such cases, the gamemaster may allow the target a POW\u215 ?1 roll to determine if some lucky incident occurs that stays the attacker\u8217's hand for the duration of the combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Big and Little Targets\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If an attacker and target are within the same relative SIZ, there are no modifiers for their attacks due to SIZ. If they are of vastly different sizes, any attacks may be modified. If the target is more than twice your character\u8217's SIZ, add +20% to your skill rating. If the target is less than half your character\u8217's size (round up), modify your skill rating by \u8211-20%. Inanimate large objects are {\i Easy} to hit, if a roll is required at all, while tiny objects are {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Both Sides Surprised\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike ambushes, situations with both sides surprised are unplanned and typically involve unaware parties on either side. Depending on the situation, the gamemaster should allow for each involved party to make an opposed Spot or Listen roll to determine who detects the other first. Everyone involved should make the roll, as some might not notice what\u8217's happening in front of them if their attention is elsewhere. In a tie, they notice each other simultaneously. To see who can act first, have each aware party make an Idea roll. If both succeed, use DEX ranks to determine who goes first.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Broken Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Equipment is often damaged or broken during combat. A weapon or shield breaks if it is used to parry an attack that reduces the weapon\u8217's hit points to 0, or through other means. A broken weapon does half its normal rolled damage (round up). Any attacks or parries with the weapon are {\i Difficult}, though the skill may be unmodified if it resembles a similar weapon with which your character is familiar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a broadsword with a blade broken in half is still useable as a shortsword. However, half of a longbow is unusable except as a light club, and a broken laser pistol is a paperweight.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Chases\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Chases occur when one party needs to outrun or outmaneuver another character, whether to avoid harm or to inflict it, or to prevent or instigate some action. Due to the variety of circumstances, chases are handled abstractly, allowing for improvisation and creative input of players and the gamemaster without requiring a map or detailed system. Whether in the open sky with jet fighters, on the busy streets of a major metropolis, or in ancient, ruined tunnels far beneath the earth\u8217's surface, all chases are handled with this system.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before beginning a chase, the gamemaster should decide these six aspects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Starting Positions:} Does one party in the chase begin with a significant advantage (a head start) or does the chase begin on relatively equal footing? Are they close to one another or already at a distance?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The Course:} How complex or hazardous is the path and how much can the participants alter the conditions? Will the environment of the chase change? Are other bystanders at risk or presenting a hazard of their own? Is the course a combination of several environments? Does the environment present a hazard or special challenges?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skills Required:} What skills can be used in this chase (e.g., Drive, Fly, or Pilot)? What powers? What skills are required if conditions of the chase change? If the vehicle suffers a malfunction, do other characters need to act to keep it running?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Combat:} Are the parties in the chase going to be attacking one another, and with what weapons or skills? Most often, these are missile weapons, but when side-by-side, hand-to-hand weapons may be used. Do other beings in the environment present a threat?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Duration:} Is there is a limitation on how long the chase will be allowed to last, such as a fixed distance before the chase will naturally end? Does fatigue play a part?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Conclusion:} What location, change of situation, or status ends the chase? This is usually obvious, but should be clear before the chase begins.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Tracking a chase uses the {\b range track} (see below). If playing together, it is useful to copy or print this out and place it on the table, or to share the image if playing online. Set the starting positions of each participant on the appropriate track relative to one another, with \u8216'lengths\u8217' equaling one full MOV in distance. Mark these positions with coins, miniatures, spare dice, or other markers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each round, all participants must make the appropriate rolls to determine how far forward (to the right) they advance. Success means that no advancement is made, while a special success means the person in the lead is moved back one step, and a critical means they are moved back two steps. If the roll is a failure, the character rolling moves back one space, and two if it is a fumble.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The goal for escaping a chase, or getting to the desired location or destination first, is to reach the \u8216'Out of Sight\u8217' square. Once someone is there at the end of the round, the chase is functionally over.\par}
