{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Choking, Drowning, and Asphyxiation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In dire circumstances, your character may be denied breathable air, such as through smoke inhalation, drowning, poisoning by gas, strangulation, or choking. All these can cause asphyxiation damage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the situation is not a surprise and is due to an environmental element, roll your character\u8217's CON\u215 ?10 (an {\i Easy} Stamina roll). If successful, your character can hold their breath during the first combat round of exposure to asphyxiation. The next round, though, the CON roll becomes CON\u215 ?5 (an unmodified Stamina roll), then is successively reduced by one multiplier each combat round after. Thus, in the third round the roll is CON\u215 ?4, then CON\u215 ?3 in the fourth round, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This continues until your character is no longer able to succeed in CON rolls, or until the roll reaches CON\u215 ?1. When the roll fails, your character takes damage total hit points at the end of each following combat round, until they escape the situation, are rendered unconscious, or die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The amount of damage depends on the substance inhaled or action being committed against your character. Inhaling water inflicts 1D8 hit points per combat round; smoke does 1D4; dense smoke does 1D6; poison gas does 1D8 plus its corrosive effect, if any. All of these go to the chest hit location, if used. Powers such as Adaptation may offer immunity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character is being deliberately choked, roll your character\u8217's CON\u215 ?1 each combat round, or take 1D6 damage to total hit points. Additionally, a strangle cord, garrote, or even strong attackers may simultaneously do basic damage to the head hit location (if used). See the Grapple skill and the weapon statistics for a garrote for more detail.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character is surprised by sudden asphyxiation, attempt a Luck roll to determine if they were able to take a breath before it began. If the roll is successful, follow the asphyxiation procedure described above (CON\u215 ?5, etc.). If the roll fails, the first roll is equal to CON\u215 ?3, then reduced each round until stopping at CON\u215 ?1. All further effects are identical to above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Close Combat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When wielding a short hand-to-hand combat weapon (SIZ 0\u8211-1.5), your character is at a slight tactical disadvantage when fighting an opponent armed with a longer hand-to-hand combat weapon (SIZ 2+). This is {\b close combat}, roughly equivalent to one meter of space around your character. For weapons like spears and polearms, the short weapon-user must first close (move into the one meter space) on their opponent to get within striking range. The following conditions apply to close combat:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In hand-to-hand combat, if the two characters are not in close combat, the gamemaster should allow a long-weapon-user to strike first against short weapon-users, regardless of DEX rank.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If a short weapon-user is in close combat with a long weapon-user, any parry attempts made by the long weapon-user are {\i Difficult}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the long weapon-user wishes, they can keep one or more short weapon-users at bay. This means that in place of an attack, the long weapon-user can attempt a normal weapon skill roll to prevent the short weapon-user(s) from closing and being able to engage in an attack in that combat round. This roll must be made each combat round, and if successful, the short weapon-user does not take any damage but cannot close during that combat round. If the long weapon-user has multiple attacks in the combat round, they can make them as normal. On subsequent combat rounds, the character with the higher DEX rank goes first, regardless of length of weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A short weapon-user being kept at bay may have to make a successful Dodge or Parry roll to get into close combat with a long weapon-user. If the attempt succeeds, they slip past the guard of the long weapon-user and can attack normally. If the Dodge or parry attempt fails, the short weapon-user is kept away from close combat for the remainder of the combat round and cannot attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Closing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In hand-to-hand combat, once an attacker {\i closes} with a target using a longer weapon (such as a spear-user attacking a sword-user), the longer weapon-user always gets the first strike regardless of DEX rank. After the initial attack by the long weapon-user, the short weapon-user can act on their normal DEX rank.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To close with a long weapon-user, a character must be closing on the target during the next combat round or next available action and may be required to make a successful Dodge roll if being kept at bay (see {\b Close Combat}, above). Though the character with the longer weapon may attack, parry, or Dodge, they may perform only one of these actions in that DEX rank. Normally a character may do two of those three actions in the same combat round, but in this case, the length of the weapon makes it less wieldy against the short weapon-user once the combat becomes close.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a long weapon-user closes with another long weapon-user, they are both limited as noted in the preceding section, but they strike at normal DEX ranks, and all subsequent combat is as normal, if they find space to wield their weapons. As noted in {\b Close Combat}, a short weapon-user can close on a long weapon-user with a successful Dodge or parry.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See also {\b Weapon Length} for more information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Cold, Exposure, Hunger, and Thirst\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When adventuring outside civilized areas, it is wise to have protective gear and carry adequate food and water to avoid the risk of succumbing to hazardous environmental conditions. If your character has purchased ample supplies, is wearing appropriate protective gear and is prepared for the terrain and the difficulties faced while traveling, your gamemaster should assume that the environment presents no special difficulty, unless a struggle for survival is an element of the scenario or campaign. If not, your character risks exposure to hazardous environments, starvation, and dehydration.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character suffers prolonged exposure to stifling heat or freezing cold, they suffer \u215 ?2\u8211-4 the normal fatigue point loss per combat round, if fatigue points are used. The gamemaster determines the multiplier for the situation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A healthy character can survive up to three days without food or water without any difficulty other than hunger and thirst. A hungry character has the same penalty for combat round activity applied to their fatigue points after two days without food, and a thirsty character must bear the penalty after one day without liquid. If the fatigue point system is not being used, any physical actions your character takes after the three-day mark are {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character has been exposed to stifling heat, freezing cold, or without food or water for 1/2 their CON in days, any physical action must be preceded by a successful Stamina roll. Failure still allows your character to perform the action, though your character takes 1 hit point in damage from the exertion. After a number of days equal to your character\u8217's CON, all rolls for Mental and Physical categories and combat rolls are {\i Difficult}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While still exposed, hungry, or thirsty, simple rest does not restore fatigue points. For every day your character\u8217's fatigue points are not a positive number, the negative value is applied directly to hit points. Furthermore, wounds take twice as long to heal after a number of days equal to your character\u8217's CON without food and/or water. In extreme cases, the gamemaster may even lower your character\u8217's SIZ characteristic by 1 or 2 points if they begin to waste away from starvation. If your character\u8217's hit points are reduced to 0 or less, they die after that day is over. The gamemaster should decide what circumstances constitute the conclusion of a day.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Powers such as Adaptation may negate the effects of exposure to extreme environments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Cover\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a target is partially covered by a wall, doorway, window ledge, fencepost, etc., any attacks on that target are {\i Difficult}. If the attack roll is over the adjusted amount to hit (but less than the normal skill rating), the attack has hit the obstacle or cover rather than the target of the attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i your character shoots at a foe half concealed behind a wall. Their normal skill rating is 72%, reduced by half to 36% because the task is }Difficult{\i . The attack strikes the target if the outcome of the roll is 36 or under. If roll falls between 37 and 72, the attack strikes the covering wall.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If appropriate, damage should be rolled to see if it bypasses the cover and goes through to the intended target of the attack (see {\b Damage to Inanimate Objects}). Roll damage only when it makes sense, such as when the attack\u8217's normal range of damage is higher than the obstacle\u8217's armor value and/or hit points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If hit locations are used, you should announce what portions of your character\u8217's body are behind cover before the gamemaster rolls for an attack, with the gamemaster deciding how much cover the obstacle allows. The attack is rolled normally, with no skill adjustments, but any protected hit locations strike the cover instead. As above, the damage rolled may pass through the covering object or structure and strike the intended target, if appropriate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Darkness\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character is fighting in darkness, whether semi-darkness or pitch black, see {\b Situational Modifiers} for modifiers. To detect an opponent in complete darkness, you must make successful {\i Difficult} Sense or Listen roll. If successful, reduce the darkness modifier by half.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character can offset the penalties of darkness by wielding a light source in one hand (see {\b Light Sources}). Powers such as Keen Sense, Aura Detection, or Super Sense may offset any darkness-related penalties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Desperate Actions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your character has performed all their actions in a combat round and yet absolutely must make one final action, at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion your character can attempt a {\b desperate action} on the last DEX rank of the round. To do so, first must make a successful {\i Difficult} Agility roll. If this fails, no action can be attempted. If successful, a desperate action is allowed. This final attack or action is always {\i Difficult}, no matter what it is. Regardless of its success, in the following round your character cannot attack or move, having unbalanced themselves with the desperate action. Dodges and parries are unaffected. If fatigue points are used, a desperate action costs double the normal fatigue points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Disarming\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes the best strategy is to remove a weapon from an opponent while in combat to stop their attacks and potentially threaten them and force a surrender. Disarming removes the target\u8217's hand weapon. Though weapons may be inadvertently broken in combat, to deliberately disarm an opponent, use one of these two methods:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Close with the target to grapple with them and wrest the weapon from their hand. Make a Grapple roll, and if successful, use a grapple effect to disarm the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab At the beginning of a round, announce the intent to disarm a target by knocking or twisting their weapon away, specifying which weapon if the target has more than one weapon. Make a {\i Difficult} attack to strike the weapon. If successful, roll damage normally and make a resistance roll vs.\u160 ?the target\u8217's STR. If the roll is successful, the target drops the weapon, taking no damage. Compare the damage rolled to the weapon\u8217's hit points: any in excess are removed from the weapon\u8217's hit points. While a successful Dodge negates a successful disarming attack, a parry of any sort has no effect. If the target suspects a disarm attack, a successful parry avoids it.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Disease\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If exposed to a minor disease, such as a bad cold or mild flu, make a Stamina roll to see if the disease is contracted. Success means that it is avoided, while failure means that your character catches the disease. For a minor disease like those above, the extent of the illness should merely cost 1 or 2 hit points and 1D6 fatigue points over a few days. On the morning of the second day your character suffers from a minor disease, roll CON\u215 ?2. If the roll is successful, your character recovers. If the roll fails, the disease persists for another day. On the morning of the third day, roll CON\u215 ?3, continuing by increasing the multiplier by the roll until the disease is finally overcome. A fumble reduces the multiplier by \u215 ?1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character must rest and be cared for while recuperating from a disease. Strenuous conditions (adventuring, combat, hard travel, etc.) reduce this characteristic roll by \u215 ?1 per outstanding condition. Thus, if the recovery roll normally would be CON\u215 ?5, reduce it to CON\u215 ?4 if your character is not at home in bed, reduce it to CON\u215 ?3 if they are hiking in the wilderness, reduce it to CON\u215 ?2 if engaged in rigorous activity such as combat, and reduce it to CON\u215 ?1 if suffering from injuries inflicted before or after the disease, another disease, or some other unfortunate medical condition.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Though medical attention may speed recovery from the disease, they must recover naturally by succeeding in the CON roll. Simply receiving medical care does not cure a disease entirely. See the Medicine skill for how treatment affects recovery. Some powers and equipment may help against disease: see {\i Chapter 4: Powers} and {\i Chapter 8: Equipment} for details.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A major disease such as plague might attack any characteristic, but most diseases attack CON or hit points. Immensely powerful diseases (such as ebola) could even inflict 1 or up to 1D3 hit points per hour, enough to kill an average human in eight hours. Symptoms vary greatly. Lesser diseases might inflict 1 hit point per day, or per week, coupled with loss of characteristic points. Cross-index the number of times your character has failed their CON roll on the {\b Illness Severity Table}.\par}
