{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Equipment with Characteristics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some equipment has characteristic values: whether values in all the characteristics, some, or only one. Some have none. This varies item to item, but if an item has a quality requiring a resistance roll, it should have a characteristic value. For equipment with characteristics, the following guidelines describe how these values work when applied to objects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Strength (STR):} An item with STR must have some means of motion. STR is not a measure of how resistant something is to STR: for that value, see its hit point or armor value. Items with STR are vehicles, construction equipment like forklifts or bulldozers, robots, or even hydraulic jacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Constitution (CON):} An item with CON is rare\u8212-hit point totals are usually based on raw SIZ and modified by armor value. Unless it can heal or is affected by disease, poison, etc. it doesn\u8217't require CON. Sample items with CON would be humanoid androids.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Size (SIZ):} SIZ is the primary characteristic for an item\u8212-almost everything has physical presence and therefore SIZ. As noted above, for most pieces of gear, SIZ determines hit point values. Sometimes an item will have greater hit points, based on what it is made of. See {\b General Qualities of Objects} for more on hit points, armor value, and other attributes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Intelligence (INT):} Rare for an item, INT represents thought, implying intuition and problem-solving. INT is unlikely for items other than computers or artificial intelligences, but magic items might have INT and attendant personalities. An item with INT should ideally have some means of communicating, such as a display, screen, voice, telepathy, or other method of relaying information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Power (POW):} POW represents spiritual energy, and is almost exclusive to living beings or magical creations. This does not represent a power source\u8212-that is either mechanical (a power point reserve) or using the Extra Energy superpower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Dexterity (DEX):} Any item capable of independent movement should have DEX. If an item with DEX must be operated by your character, use the lower DEX of either your character or the item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Charisma (CHA):} While CHA has elements of personality and personal charisma included, for an item it can either be the aesthetic appeal, or it may represent that the item is capable of communication and charm. The main reason to assign CHA to an inanimate item is to compare its appearance to another item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Education (EDU) (Option):} Aside from representing training or downloaded knowledge for a thinking computer, EDU is best used for equipment with knowledge reserves. Usually such an item either adds a bonus to your character\u8217's Research skill, or can make skill rolls {\i Easy} or {\i Difficult}. When assigned to an item, EDU stands for data it has immediate access to. This figure expands dramatically with the advent of information storage and online access to databases.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As noted above, it isn\u8217't essential for each piece of equipment or item to have characteristics unless they\u8217're needed. If in the course of play, you need a value that hasn\u8217't been defined, generate it with a roll of an appropriate number of D6s or assign it a value based on similar pieces of equipment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You could even determine the value with a Status roll: a fumble is a value of 1, a failure equals 1D6, a success equals 2D6, a special success is 2D6+6, and a critical success gives the item a characteristic of 2D6+12.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Equipment with Skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some equipment may possess skills, handled just like character skills. Any piece of equipment capable of independent action can have a skill. Some examples might be automated defense systems with the Artillery skill; educational programs using Teach; diagnostic systems using Repair; etc. In general, the more intelligent piece of equipment is, the more likely it is to have one or more skills.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your gamemaster should set the values of these skills, based on the nature of the piece of equipment. If it has a characteristic related to the skill (for example, INT and Knowledge skills), its skill level may be a multiple of that characteristic (\u215 ?1, \u215 ?3, \u215 ?5, etc.), depending on how efficient it is. {\b Other Equipment} provides examples of equipment with skills. If the item can speak or read, it should have a Language skill\u8212-usually the owner\u8217's or creator\u8217's native language.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To begin play with an item possessing skills, \u8216'pay\u8217' for the item\u8217's skill points out of your character\u8217's personal skill point pool (from {\b Step Seven} of character creation) or the professional pool if the item is important to the performance of their profession.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Alternately, you can treat the item as if it had superpowers (see {\i Chapter 4: Powers}) and purchase the item as if it were a power. In this case, the following conditions apply:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The item has the character failing \u8220"Superpowered identity must be turned on in an obvious and preventable manner\u8221" tied to the item, usually a +1 power budget bonus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Other power failings may apply, such as \u8220"Power has a limited number of uses per day\u8221" or \u8220"Power cannot improve through experience.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Skills are purchased with the Super Skill power. It is assumed that all items have a 0% starting skill rating.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If no obvious attributes exist for the item, work with your gamemaster to determine its power supply, range, etc. Additional superpowers can be purchased to improve these attributes.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you invest points in an item, you are going to want to have it available. Your gamemaster should do whatever they can to make sure that your item survives with your character, is readily repairable, or a replacement can be found easily, as appropriate to its value and the setting. Despite the fact that it is a distinct item, it is considered to be a part of your character, just as another character\u8217's skill or power is, and removing it from your character\u8217's possession should be done with extreme care, unless unavoidable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Items with skills do not increase their skill rating through successful use of experience, unless the item has an INT and your gamemaster determines that it is capable of learning in some fashion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Equipment with Powers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A piece of equipment can have properties above and beyond its normal capabilities, and with your gamemaster \u8217's permission, your character can purchase an item or piece of equipment with a power as described in {\i Chapter 4: Powers}. Additionally, your gamemaster may choose to represent a piece of equipment in terms of a power for ease determining its effectiveness against a powered character, and vice versa. This is usually only necessary in campaigns using powers, as normally the base attributes for an item are enough.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Following are guidelines for powered equipment, based on the power systems in {\i Chapter 4: Powers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Magic Items:} A piece of equipment with one or more magic spells is called a {\i magic item}. This item appears magical to anyone able to detect such things, and allows the owner to cast a magic spell as if they were able to cast it themself. The magic item must have a skill rating with the spell. Most magic items have a power point capacity of their own, while rarer magic items use the owner\u8217's power points as the reservoir.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A magic item is useless if it reaches 0 power points, though it can be recharged. To recharge a magic item, the user can move 1 power point from their body into the magic item each combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A magic item can hold up to double its maximum power points. These extra power points vanish as they do with a player character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any spells the item casts follow all rules regarding the particular spell.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When the magic item is created, your gamemaster should determine whether if only the creator can use it, it must be defeated in a power point vs.\u160 ?power point resistance roll, or if anyone can use it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The item has the normal hit points (based on SIZ) and attributes of an appropriate non-magical version.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The item\u8217's hit points limit the number of power points it can store. As it takes damage, the maximum power points it can store are reduced. The item can be repaired normally, though if it is broken or destroyed, it is no longer magic and remains a normal item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If a magic item is destroyed, any POW spent on it are lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A magic item may have one or more permanent magic spells bound into it that are always active, but creation of such an item costs five times the normal POW cost. Your gamemaster should determine whether a magic spell can be cast permanently on an item. If this item is created, it does not require power points and is simply always on at full strength.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mutated Items:} Items with mutations are fairly rare, as mutations are traditionally caused through genetic variance and few inanimate items are created through genetic manipulation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab An item can have one or more adverse mutations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The item has the normal hit points (based on SIZ) and other attributes of a normal version, unless the mutation affects these characteristics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any characteristic rolls the item must make are based on the creator\u8217's characteristics if it does not have its own characteristic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A mutated item is considered to be alive and heals at the same rate as its creator.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A mutated item can be used by anyone making a successful Stamina roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any CON and mutations invested into a mutated item are lost if it is destroyed.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Equipment with Psychic Abilities:} Items with psychic abilities are incredibly rare, even more than items with mutations. These items are inevitably charged with psychic power, and should at least have POW. A character with any psychic ability automatically recognizes that an item has psychic abilities, and with an Idea roll, can utilize it. A character without psychic abilities can only determine if an item has psychic properties with a successful Idea roll, and must either defeat the item in a power point vs.\u160 ?power point resistance roll or a {\i Difficult} Luck roll. The creator of the item (or your gamemaster) decides who can use the item .\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The item has the normal hit points (based on SIZ) and other attributes of a normal version of that item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Psychic items are not alive, and can be damaged. They do not naturally heal, but can be repaired with an appropriate Craft or Repair skill roll. When they are destroyed they cease functioning. If a psychic item is broken into more than one piece, your gamemaster decides which piece, if any, retains the psychic ability.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Equipment with Sorcery:} A piece of equipment with one or more sorcery spells is called an {\b artifact}. This artifact appears to have sorcerous properties to anyone able to detect such things, and allows your character to cast a sorcery spell as if they could cast it themselves, or the item has the sorcery spell cast upon itself permanently. Most artifacts have a power point reservoir of their own, while rarer artifacts draw upon the user\u8217's own power points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The creator of an artifact must sacrifice 1 point of permanent POW per sorcery spell invested in the artifact, and must know or have access to the spell(s) the artifact can use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The artifact has a power point reservoir equal to its creator\u8217's normal power points after it is created, or its SIZ, whichever is larger. Your gamemaster should set the POW and power point capacity if the artifact\u8217's creator is unknown or is a nonplayer character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The artifact either goes \u8216'unconscious\u8217' when at 0 power points, or will be inert. To recharge an artifact, the user can move 1 power point from their body into the artifact each combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab An artifact can contain more than its normal power point capacity, as per a character, up to double its maximum power points. These extra power points vanish as they do with a character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any sorcery spells cast from the artifact follow all the normal rules regarding the particular spell.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When the artifact is created, your gamemaster should determine whether it will be personal (only its creator can use it), whether it must be defeated in a power point vs.\u160 ?power point resistance roll if it has power points, or if anyone can use it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The artifact has the normal hit points (based on SIZ) and attributes of an appropriate non-sorcerous version.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The artifact\u8217's hit points limit the number of power points that can be stored in it. As it takes damage, the maximum power points it stores are reduced. The artifact can be repaired as a normal item, though if it is broken or destroyed it can never be restored to artifact status and will remain a non-sorcerous item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If an artifact is destroyed, any POW invested in it are lost.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some artifacts have permanent sorcery spells bound into them that are always active. The POW cost to create these items is doubled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Equipment with Superpowers:} A piece of equipment with superpowers is called a gadget. Gadgets are the most flexible of all types of powered item, and can look like anything; mundane or crude to vastly advanced. A gadget\u8217's appearance is entirely cosmetic and has nothing to do with its function: it can glow, shine, emit strange trails of energy, be carved with ancient runes, etc. A gadget does not seem unusually powerful unless the creator wants it to. Your gamemaster should set the power level of the gadget using the campaign power level guidelines presented in {\i Chapter 4: Powers}. Your gamemaster should assign any levels of superpowers to any gadget as desired, to suit the setting and the item\u8217's requirements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following rules apply to gadgets:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The gadget\u8217's hit points, SIZ, etc. are based off a normal item of equivalent size and mass. If no obvious equivalent exists, use the {\b Object SIZ Examples} table and the {\b Armor} table for guidelines. To change its size, use the Size Change power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the gadget needs a characteristic (such as POW for power points) should be built with the Super Characteristic power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A gadget requiring a power supply greater than its POW should have the Extra Energy power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To make the gadget more durable than a normal item, give it superpowers such as Absorption, Armor, Extra Hit Points, Force Field, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whenever applicable, the gadget should rely on its own characteristics. If a power requires a resistance roll, the gadget\u8217's characteristic (if any) should be used. If the gadget doesn\u8217't have the relevant characteristic, it automatically fails the resistance roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whenever applicable, the gadget should rely on its user\u8217's relevant skill.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i if the gadget is a pistol, it must be fired with the Firearm skill. If it is a cosmically powered bracelet that allows the wielder to fire radioactive blasts, use the Projection skill.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your gamemaster should examine any superpowered items to be sure that they are not overly powered or otherwise unbalancing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Superpowers invested in a gadget are permanent unless the item is destroyed.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Equipment with Multiple Power Types:} Your gamemaster may wish to create a powered item drawing from multiple power types, such as a gadget that is also an artifact, using superpowers and sorcery. These should be only available at your gamemaster\u8217's discretion. The following principles apply:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When possible, treat the item as being created as if it were a player with multiple power types.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab An item must have all relevant characteristics or skills to use any powers it has.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab All powers draw from the same pool of resources, whether power points or another source. Recharging the item must be handled in the appropriate manner for each power set.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If for some reason an item has two values to choose from to perform a particular action, use the higher of the two values where appropriate.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Equipment with Requirements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some types of equipment may have requirements that must be met or exceeded to be used by your character. An example is weaponry, where most weapons have a minimum STR and DEX requirement. Other types of equipment are limited in other ways, such as the high fatigue point demand from wearing armor, and skill penalties associated with it. None of the basic equipment in this chapter have any requirements, though your gamemaster can easily introduce a restriction on the use of an item in two obvious ways:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Characteristics:} As with weapons, a piece of equipment may be restricted by your characteristics. Usually this is STR or DEX, such as with weapons, or SIZ for armor, but it could easily be POW for a magical item, INT for a computer, or some other characteristic-based minimum (or maximum).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skills:} Your character may find that a specific piece of equipment is incomprehensible or useless unless their skill is at a certain level. Usually the skill represents an understanding of the piece of equipment and the principles it operates under.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i a diagnostic computer may require a skill of at least 50% in Technical (Computer Use) to operate.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is recommended that restrictions be used sparingly, and only if there is a legitimate reason for them to exist. Before assigning an outright restriction on an item\u8217's use, your gamemaster should determine if there is some means of enforcing the restriction, and if there are any penalties for using the item if your character does not meet the requirements. Some possible penalties include additional fatigue points to use, making any associated skill rolls {\i Difficult}, or requiring an associated characteristic roll to avoid mishaps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Charges or Limited-Use Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many types of equipment run on power batteries or can be used only a limited number of times. In most cases batteries can be replaced fairly easily, ammunition replenished, and other required resources recharged or refilled. Most firearms have \u8216'charges\u8217' in the form of ammunition, but if maintained well, a sword or suit of armor can be used until it is broken. Whenever appropriate, the resource required to refill or recharge a piece of equipment is either essentially free (such as electricity or solar power), or is two or three Wealth levels lower than the equipment\u8217's cost. If a charging device is required, it is a part of the piece of equipment\u8217's normal value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Usually it\u8217's easiest to assume that given adequate time and planning, your character has adequate ammunition, batteries, refills, cartridges, power cells, etc. for all their gear, unless the setting or circumstances make this is difficult or impossible. In these cases, your gamemaster may require a Research, Status, or Luck roll to come across the relevant type of charge. In some settings (postapocalyptic, for example) ammunition, gasoline, and/or power cells are extremely difficult to come by and are usually more valuable than the equipment they\u8217're used in.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Repairing Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If an item has been damaged in the course of play, your gamemaster should determine if it can be repaired, based on common sense and the nature of the damage dealt. In most cases, a relevant Repair or Craft skill roll may be used like the First Aid skill, restoring damaged hit points or SIZ points as per the guidelines for that skill. In the case of complex equipment, your gamemaster may require a Knowledge roll to find a resource for replacement components, or even require an {\i Easy} skill roll based on the repair skill being used to locate the necessary parts. If these components are expensive, your gamemaster may require a Status roll to legitimately obtain required replacements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Throughout history, many different types of weapons have developed as a result of changes in technology, availability of materials, and changing battlefield conditions. This section presents a representative sampling of this wide variety. If your gamemaster wishes to create more accurate weapon lists for a setting, it is easy enough to extrapolate the relevant attributes from these examples.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Weapons described in this section are categorized broadly by chronological settings for ease of use. In most cases, weapons from an earlier period are available to people from later periods, so your gamemaster may simply choose where weapon availability stops and allow your character access to weapons prior to that point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each weapon has the following attributes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Name:} The common name for the weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skill:} The skill used to wield it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Base:} The base chance to use the weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Dmg:} The damage done by the weapon. A \u8216'+dm\u8217' indicates damage modifier, and +\u189 ?dm is half the damage modifier (round up).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Attk:} How many attacks-per-round does the weapon allow?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} What type of special success does the weapon do?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Rng:} The basic range of the weapon. At its basic range, the skill is unmodified. At medium range (double the basic range), the skill use becomes {\i Difficult}, and at long range (four times basic range) it becomes 1/5 the normal skill rating (equal to the chance of a special).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Hands:} How many hands does the weapon require? 1H=one-handed, 2H=two-handed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b HP:} The weapon\u8217's hit points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Parry:} Can the weapon be used to parry?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Mal:} The weapon malfunctions if this is rolled (see {\b Malfunctions}). If the weapon is not a firearm, the malfunction is some other mishap preventing immediate reuse of the weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Ammo:} How many times can the weapon be used without being reloaded or recharged?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Value:} What is the weapon\u8217's average cost in an appropriate setting?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b STR/DEX:} What are the minimum STR and DEX required to use the weapon?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b SIZ/ENC:} The weapon\u8217's SIZ and Encumbrance value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b RF:} (Optional) Rate of fire (see {\b Volley Fire}). 1/#CR means that the weapon is so clumsy it can only be used once a number (#) of combat rounds. X/CR means that it can be used X times per combat round when using volley fire.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Weapon Descriptions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Following are all weapons from the melee and missile weapon tables, organized alphabetically.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Arbalest:} A very heavy crossbow, difficult to cock and load, often used with a device called a cranequin. It does tremendous damage when it hits.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Axe, Battle:} A one-handed axe used primarily in combat. It may have one blade or two.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Axe, Great:} A large, two-handed axe that either may be single or double-bladed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Axe, Hand:} A small one-handed axe that can be thrown or used by hand. It may have one blade or two. Tool versions are used to chop wood.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Axe, Vibro-:} A long-handled axe with one or two blades mounted into a generator in the haft. The blades vibrate at an extraordinary rate, capable of shearing through most substances.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Axe, Wood:} A long-handled axe that can be used one- or two-handed, with one blade or two. It is not built for combat, but is sometimes utilized so.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Blackjack:} A small sewn leather sack full of something heavy like lead shot, used to knock someone out when attacking from behind. Also called a sap or cosh.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Blowgun:} A hollow, straight pipe up to a meter in length used to project small darts by blowing at one end of the pipe. These darts do little damage but are often poisoned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bola:} Two or three hard balls attached together by a length of cord or chain. This weapon is thrown to entangle and bring down a foe, with damage a secondary concern.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Boomerang:} A flat, angle-shaped stick made to be thrown in a curving path. It was traditionally used by aboriginal hunters to stun or kill small animals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bow, Composite:} A bow made of materials that make it both rigid and flexible. Historical versions are made of wood and horn, and modern varieties are made with graphite and ultralight metals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bow, Long:} A bow made either from one piece of wood (such as the famous English longbow), or in the same fashion as a composite bow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bow, Self:} A basic bow made of one or two pieces of wood shaped and cured to prevent breaking.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Brass Knuckles:} Metal weights worn on the fist to add weight and a hard edge to punches.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Cestus:} Metal boxing gloves, with a weight nestled within the glove for more impact. An ancient precursor to brass knuckles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Chainsaw:} A woodcutting tool consisting of an edged chain driven to revolve at high speed around a flat metal blade.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Claw:} A bladed weapon shaped like animal claws, usually held in hand with the blades sticking through the fingers, or worn on the back of the hand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Club, Heavy:} A long heavy piece of wood or metal. This also describes a crowbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Club, Light:} A lighter version of the heavy club. This can be a baseball bat, tire iron, lamp, chair leg, or truncheon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crossbow, Heavy:} This crossbow must be cocked by a lever apparatus. Easier to load than an arbalest, but less powerful.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crossbow, Light:} This crossbow can be cocked by hand, mostly used for hunting or stealth, rather than on the battlefield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crossbow, Medium:} This crossbow is cocked by hooking one end with a foot and using a claw mechanism to draw the string back.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crossbow, Repeating:} A complex crossbow with a magazine of bolts that may be fired as fast as a bow may be fired. Once the magazine is exhausted, the repeating crossbow takes at least six combat rounds to reload.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dagger:} A short-bladed weapon, usually less than 40 centimeters long, sharp on one or both edges.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dart:} Short, weighted points suitable for throwing, either feathered or plain. They are often used to deliver poison.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Detonator, Antimatter:} Perhaps the most powerful personal-scale explosive, this can wipe out everything in a tight radius. These are used with timers, coded remote detonators, and magnetic bases.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Detonator, Electromagnetic Pulse:} Instead of exploding, this device emits an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) designed to disrupt electrical devices and electronic circuitry. Unlike the EMP generated as a secondary effect of a nuclear weapon, this is a non-nuclear electromagnetic pulse, disruptive solely to electronic devices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Detonator, Fusion:} An extremely powerful sub-nuclear bomb, capable of immense destructive force. Comes with a timer, coded remote detonator, and magnetic base.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Detonator, Plasma:} An explosive capable of generating and spraying a charge of plasma, the superheated intermediate state between gas and liquid. These come with timers, coded remote detonators, and magnetic bases.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Detonator, Sonic:} A device that emits a destructive and concussive sonic pulse that can shatter glass and other brittle matter, as well as stunning any living targets caught in its range of effect.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Explosive, Blasting Cap:} A small explosive used to set off a larger explosive. Older ones used fuses, while newer ones use electricity or more sophisticated methods to set off the explosive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Explosive, Dynamite:} Sticks of chemical explosive soaked into a solid like sawdust, wrapped in thick paper and ignited by sparks from a fuse or a smaller explosion from a blasting cap. This is highly dangerous, as it tends to \u8216'sweat\u8217' nitroglycerine and becomes unstable when left alone for too long.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Explosive, Improvised:} Usually a pipe bomb, this describes any number of small homemade chemical explosives.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Explosive, Plastic:} A modern chemical explosive mixed with a substance like petroleum or wax into a malleable, putty-like plastic form, able to be molded and shaped as required. Used with a timer and often set off with an electrical charge. Also called plastique.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fist:} An unarmed attack using the Brawl skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flail:} A flail head mounted on the end of a short chain connected to a haft about a meter long, or longer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flail, Morningstar:} A medieval weapon with a handle, a length of chain, and a spiked ball at the end. Some do not have spikes and are simply weighted or studded balls at the end of the chains.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flamethrower:} A tank full of a highly combustible chemical attached to a projector/igniter that sprays jets of flaming liquid. Flamethrowers can also be used to soak an area or item in this flammable chemical without setting it afire. Incredibly dangerous due to the short range, limited period of use, and potential for setting oneself on fire. Flamethrowers may blow up when the tank is struck, causing double rolled damage to everyone within five meters of the user. Make a Luck roll to avoid this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Garrote:} A short cord used for strangling, whether a thin metal cable, ceremonial rope, to improvised use of a scarf or belt.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gauntlet, Armored:} A metal gauntlet worn with armor or without, adding damage to successful strikes with the Brawl skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grapple:} An unarmed attack using the Grapple skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Antimatter:} A small but extraordinarily powerful explosive device triggered and thrown at foes, items, or structures. Though containing infinitely tiny amounts of antimatter, these grenades are usually fired from launchers, as they are so destructive that it is difficult to throw one outside of its own blast radius.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Concussion:} A small explosive device triggered and thrown at foes or into enclosed areas, where it can stun those caught in the blast radius. Sometimes called a stun grenade.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Disintegrator:} A grenade capable of disintegrating all of the matter (or shattering molecular bonds) in the blast radius. Highly dangerous, disintegrator grenades are generally used only as weapons of last resort.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Electromagnetic Pulse:} A grenade with electromagnetic pulse capability. When thrown at a metallic target, the magnetic surface add +20% to your chance of hitting successfully.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Explosive:} A small explosive triggered and thrown, resulting in an explosion of concussive force and shrapnel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Flare:} A stick of flammable chemicals triggered and thrown to light darkened areas or provide light-marking for air targeting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Fusion:} An extremely powerful sub-nuclear device, capable of immense destructive force. Fusion grenades are only fired from launchers or thrown in situations where the user has adequate time to get out of the blast range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Gas:} A small chemical explosive device triggered and thrown or rolled, emitting a toxic or otherwise harmful gas. These can be filled with a variety of gases (mustard, tear, knockout, etc.).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Molotov Cocktail:} An improvised explosive made from a bottle and fuse, lit and hurled, usually to set them or it afire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Phosphorous:} A small chemical explosive device triggered and thrown. It emits a highly flammable chemical fire that can melt equipment and set objects aflame, or simply light a darkened area for ground personnel or targeting from airships.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Plasma:} A grenade using plasma technology. Extremely explosive and capable of causing immense destruction and fire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Shock:} A grenade that releases an electrical charge, equipped with magnetic surfaces to stick to any metallic surface it is thrown onto. When thrown at a metallic target, the magnetic surface adds +20% to your chance of hitting successfully.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Shrapnel:} A small explosive device triggered and thrown at enemies, set to emit deadly, flesh-piercing shrapnel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Smoke:} A gas grenade (see above) that emits harmless but shrouding smoke.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Sonic:} A grenade using sonic pulse technology that emits a high-frequency sonic burst to disable or distract targets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Grenade, Stun:} A grenade emitting a mildly concussive blast designed specifically to stun or temporarily disable targets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gun, Machine:} A rapidly-repeating firearm with trigger settings for single-shot, short bursts, and full autofire.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gun, Mini-:} A Gatling-style heavy machine gun, often mounted on helicopters or vehicles. The STR requirement is if wielded in hand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gun, Submachine:} A small machine gun, designed for one-handed use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Halberd:} An broad axe head on a two-meter shaft. Commonly used by medieval city guardsmen or against mounted foes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hammer:} A common household tool used for carpentry or a small, one-handed military weapon with a striking head.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hammer, Great:} A massive hammer used with two hands.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hammer, Sledge:} A heavy tool used by construction workers and demolition crews, used two-handed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hammer, War:} Designed like a hammer, this weapon often has a spike rather than a flat head, ideal for punching through armor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Head Butt:} An unarmed attack using the Brawl skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Javelin:} A short spear used one- or two-handed, or for throwing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Katana:} A single-edged, slightly curved long sword, used one- or two-handed, fetishized for its workmanship and sharpness.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Kick:} An unarmed attack using the Brawl skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife:} A tool suitable for eating, cutting, defense, or impromptu assassination. Like a dagger, though lighter and less durable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife, Butcher:} A large heavy kitchen knife, suitable for hacking through large chunks of meat in a single blow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife, Pocket:} A small folding knife, often with multiple blades.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife, Switchblade:} A retractable pocketknife.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife, Throwing:} A knife balanced for throwing, usually hiltless.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knife, Vibro:} A high-tech knife blade set into a mechanical hilt, vibrated at an extremely high speed. Extraordinarily sharp, the vibration adds additional shearing force to even slight cuts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lance:} A long spear used one-handed on horseback. While mounted, the attacker uses the mount\u8217's damage modifier in place of their own. Lances can also be used on foot as a two-handed spear, with its normal damage modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lance, Stun:} A staff-shaped weapon with a charged electric prod at one end. Some stun lances have goads at both ends.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lasso:} The traditional lariat used for cattle-wrangling. It does no damage but does immobilize the target using the entangling rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Launcher, Grenade:} A hand-held or stationary launcher that fires grenades great distances. It can be a small platform, a hand-held firearm-shaped launcher, or attached to another firearm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Launcher, LAW Rocket:} A lightweight, disposable one-shot rocket launcher, also known as the light anti-tank weapon (LAW).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Launcher, Rocket:} A smallish tube and platform assembled on the battlefield, used to fire rockets more accurately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mace, Heavy:} A haft with a heavy weight for the head, spiked, flanged, studded, or plain.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mace, Light:} A haft with a light weight used to bash and crush.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Maul, War:} A long-handled two-headed hammer used two-handed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mine, Antipersonnel:} A land mine built primarily to wound rather than kill (maximizing difficulty to the enemy).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mine, Antitank:} A mine made to damage tank treads or enemy vehicles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Naginata:} A long spear with a sword-like head, used for cutting and thrusting attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Net:} A loose mesh of woven cord used to catch animals or larger targets. While smaller nets are used for small game, the net described here is large enough for use against humans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pike:} A long spear (3\u8211-5 meters) used in formation combat. Also common to town guards and castle defense. Pikes are the best defense (short of a fusillade of gunfire) against a cavalry charge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Blaster:} A pistol firing a short burst of energy, usually plasma, burning the target and causing concussion. Blaster pistols are usually powered by clips containing exotic chemical fuels.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Derringer:} A tiny hand-held pistol, usually palm-sized. Easily concealed, with a low ammo capacity. Some are one- or two-shot, others have small clips. Sometimes called a \u8216'holdout\u8217' pistol.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Disintegrator:} A pistol firing an immensely destructive energy blast that rapidly disintegrates an entire target, or large portions of that target. Disintegrator pistols can be powered with energy cells or fuel clips.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Electromagnetic Pulse:} A pistol that fires a directed electromagnetic pulse stream at a target such as a computer or robot, disabling its circuitry.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Flechette:} A small, light pistol powered by either magnetic charges or gas, firing many tiny, sharp needle-like blades at a target. These generally have short range and are not very effective against armored targets, but are devastating to unarmored foes at short range. They use both clips of flechette ammunition and a gas cylinder or energy clip. Sometimes called a \u8216'needle gun\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Flintlock:} A pistol using flint and steel to ignite a hand-packed wad of gunpowder. Similar to a wheel-lock pistol.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Heavy:} A heavy-framed pistol possessing superior stopping power. Slower than smaller, lighter pistols. The .357 magnum is an excellent example.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Laser:} A pistol firing a high-intensity beam of light capable of searing through most substances, even melting metal. Usually powered by an energy cell containing a limited number of charges.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Light:} A light-framed pistol trading stopping power for accuracy and rate of fire. The .22 caliber is an excellent example.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Medium:} A medium-framed pistol, reliable and with moderate firepower and rate of fire. The 9mm pistol is an excellent example.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Plasma:} A pistol firing a focused stream of superheated plasma, usually powered by an energy or plasma cell.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Shock:} A pistol that emits a high-voltage electrical burst.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Sonic:} A pistol emitting a focused cone of sonic waves, damaging to living tissue and inert matter alike.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pistol, Stun:} A pistol emitting a burst of energy the same frequency as the human nervous system, short-ranged and designed for pacification. Useless against objects and beings larger than humanoid, though they can be adjusted for other targets. Sometimes called a \u8216'stunner\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rapier:} A slender-bladed one-handed sword, primarily used for thrusting. Though each is unique, this also describes the epee and foil, two other fencing swords.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Revolver, Heavy:} A heavy pistol of large caliber, like a .44 magnum or the Colt .45.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Revolver, Light:} A light pistol, usually in the .22 to .32 caliber range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Revolver, Medium:} A medium pistol, usually .357 to .38 caliber.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Assault:} A heavy, rugged rifle with a large ammo capacity, fired like a machine gun (one-shot, short bursts, or autofire).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Blaster:} A rifle firing short energy bursts, usually plasma that burns plus concussive impact. Blaster rifles are usually powered by clips containing exotic chemical fuels.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Bolt-action:} A rifle with a sliding bolt. Some use clips, while others store bullets in magazines the length of the rifle\u8217's barrel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Disintegrator:} A rifle that emits an immensely destructive energy blast that rapidly disintegrates an entire target or large portions of that target. Disintegrator rifles can be powered with energy cells or fuel clips.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Elephant:} A huge caliber rifle designed to bring down the largest of game animals. Sometimes double-barreled, these often are breech-loaded, one thick bullet at a time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Laser:} A rifle firing a high-intensity beam of light capable of searing through most substances, even melting metal. Laser rifles are usually powered by energy cells with limited charges.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Lever-action:} A rifle with an external lever used to cycle ammo. Popular with hunters, though impractical for military use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Musket:} An early rifle loaded down the barrel and sometimes filled with either shrapnel shot or large ball-like bullets. Slow and unreliable, ignited with a flint or wheel-lock.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Electromagnetic Pulse:} A rifle version of the electromagnetic pulse pistol, emitting a focused blast of electromagnetic energy at an electric-using or electronic target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Plasma:} A rifle version of a plasma pistol, capable of firing a focused burst of superheated plasma at the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Shock:} A rifle version of the shock pistol, capable of firing a lightning-like blast for considerable range and power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Sonic:} A rifle version of the sonic pistol, firing a cone-like sonic pulse blast at the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Sniper:} A long-barreled rifle used for long-range fire, precision-calibrated and usually equipped with a long-range scope.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Sporting:} A light- to medium-caliber (.22 or .30\u8211-06) rifle used to bring down smaller game animals like deer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rifle, Stun:} A rifle emitting a short-ranged energy burst in the same frequency as the human nervous system, meant for pacification. Useless against objects and beings larger than humanoid, a stun rifle can be adjusted for other targets. Sometimes called a \u8216'stunner\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rock, Thrown:} The most basic weapon, a fist-sized rock.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Saber:} A single-edged, curved sword, used most commonly by mounted cavalry and in fencing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sai:} A dagger-like weapon shaped like a trident, with a wide curved crossbar. Sai have no edge and are used as clubs, stabbing weapons, or sword-breakers. They are often used paired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scimitar:} A single-edged, slightly curved, heavy-bladed sword.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scythe:} A long-handled farming tool with a curved blade set perpendicular to the haft, used for harvesting grains, but occasionally with ceremonial purpose.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Shotgun, Automatic:} A shotgun with a large ammo capacity and automatic loading, usually for battlefield or police action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Shotgun, Double-barreled:} A breech-loading shotgun.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Shotgun, Sawed-off:} A sporting or double-barreled shotgun with a shorter barrel, hand-altered or manufactured for ease of concealment and convenience. The shorter barrel trades range for wider dispersal of ammo.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Shotgun, Sporting:} A medium- to light-gauge shotgun (16- or 20-gauge), used for hunting and home protection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Shuriken:} Small throwing blades, often star-shaped. Easily concealed and a favorite of assassins.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sickle:} A crescent-shaped flat blade, single-edged on the inside crescent, used one-handed to harvest grain or ceremonial purposes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sling:} A leather thong with a cup or recess to hold a rock or sling stone, whirled and thrown with incredible force at the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Spear, Long:} A length of wood roughly two meters long, with a metal- or flint-bladed head or a fire-hardened point. These must be used two-handed. Characters armed with long spears often strike first in a combat round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Spear, Short:} A length of wood roughly 1.5 meters long, with a metal- or flint- bladed head or a fire-hardened point. Short spears can be used one-or two-handed, or thrown.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Spray, Chemical:} A chemical irritant projected from small a sprayer usually into a target\u8217's eyes. Short-range and nonlethal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Staff, Quarter:} A long wooden staff often used as a walking staff, useful for defense and attacking.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Staff, Short:} A short, narrow wooden club like a police truncheon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword Cane:} A thin-bladed sword disguised to fit inside a cane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Bastard:} A straight, single-or double-edged sword, over a meter long, with a long hilt wielded one-or two-handed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Broad:} A straight, single- or double-edged sword around a meter long, used one-handed. Some have basket hilts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Energy:} A hilt containing a shaped field emitter that projects a sword-length blade of energy, like a beam of focused light. Energy swords use power packs, and often require expensive or rare focusing crystals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Great:} A straight, double-edged sword almost two meters long, used two-handed, often against pike formations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Long:} A straight, single- or double-edged sword, sometimes with a basket hilt, used one-handed. Lighter and slenderer than a broadsword.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Monofilament:} An sophisticated weapon consisting of a blade exactly one molecule thick, set into stasis by a generator in the hilt. With the blade able to slip between atoms, it is capable of cutting through almost anything. As the blade is almost invisible, it is extremely difficult to use, and a fumble may be fatal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Short:} A single or double-edged sword, usually a half-meter long.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sword, Vibro:} A longer version of a vibro knife. A handle containing a long sword-like blade vibrated at an high speed, capable of shearing through most substances.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Taser, Contact:} A small hand-held electric device designed to disrupt the neural activity of the target, stunning them momentarily.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Taser, Dart:} A hand-held taser that fires two small darts with attached wires. Once these hit their target, the taser emits a disruptive electrical charge that usually stuns or incapacitates.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Torch:} A thick stick of wood with one end soaked in pitch or some other fuel, occasionally wrapped in rags. Ignited and used for light, torches are often wielded as improvised weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Trident:} A three-tined spear, like a fork, with curving side-prongs. Tridents usually have barbed points to hook into their target\u8217's flesh.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Wakizashi:} A short sword version of the katana, often made as a matching pair. Some have small knives built into their scabbards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Whip:} A coiled and woven leather rope with a handle at one end, used to lash an opponent or catch and immobilize a limb (see {\b Entangling}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Whip, Shock:} A metallic whip that generates a high-voltage electric current, released onto the target when it strikes successfully.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Weapon Classes\par}
