{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Shields\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Shields are basically large parrying weapons, designed to be interposed between your character and an attacker. A shield usually has a handle, strap, or straps and is worn on the non-weapon arm (for most people, the left arm). Traditionally, shields must compromise between toughness, lightness, and balance. Shields range in size from the small buckler (barely the size of a dinner plate) to the large shield used by Hoplite warriors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Shields are categorized chronologically. In most cases, shields from an earlier period are available in later periods, so your gamemaster may simply choose where availability stops and allow your character access to shields prior to that point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All shields are used in melee or to defend against missiles. A thrown shield is an improvised weapon with a range of 10 meters and a 05% chance to hit (this can increase with experience).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each shield type has the following attributes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Name:} The common name for the shield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Base Chance:} The base chance for anyone picking up the shield. This base chance is also the beginning value for attacking with the shield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skill:} The skill used for the shield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b AV/HP:} This is the shield\u8217's armor point value as well as its hit point value. This amount is used if the shield is damaged or targeted. See Slung Shields (following) for details.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Damage:} The amount of damage the shield does if used as a weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special:} The type of special success the shield does. Most shields do knockback special successes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Burden:} This describes the awkwardness or relative encumbrance of the shield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b ENC:} (Optional) The ENC value of the shield.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Locations:} (Optional) For hit locations, the hit locations covered by the shield. This is usually only appropriate for slung shields. See {\b Slung Shields}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b STR/DEX:} The minimum STR and DEX required to use the shield. If your character does not meet the minimum required STR and DEX, any uses of the shield are Difficult.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Value:} The shield\u8217's cost in an appropriate setting.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each shield type is described in {\b Shield Descriptions}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Slung Shields\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Usually shields are worn slung over the arm/shoulder or back when not being used actively in combat. If your gamemaster is using hit locations, add 1/2 the armor value of a slung shield (round up) to any hit location struck by a weapon, in addition to the armor value already in that location. Of the shields described in this section, only the buckler, primitive, and energy shields cannot be slung. As most shields have a high armor value, this negates most attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b {\i For example,}} {\i your character has a shield slung over their back, and an opponent fires an arrow from behind. The attack is a success, and the hit location rolled indicates the torso. Your gamemaster rules that the shield covers this hit location, so \u189 ? of the shield\u8217's armor value is applied to the arrow\u8217's damage. Your gamemaster tells you \u8220"The arrow thuds into the shield on your back, but it doesn\u8217't get through.\u8221" Now your character has a chance to hold their shield properly, not trusting another lucky break.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Shield Descriptions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This section describes all types of shields, organized alphabetically.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Buckler:} A small shield that protects the lower part of the arm, usually held with a handgrip or single strap. These are worn on the belt (or swash), which gave rise to the term \u8216'swashbuckler\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Energy Shield:} A defensive device consisting of a small power pack mounted on the defender\u8217's arm and a projector that emits a circular shield of variable size.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Full Shield:} Larger than a small shield and of a variety of shapes, a full shield is usually large enough to cover the defender\u8217's lower face and groin.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Half Shield:} A smaller shield of a variety of shapes, commonly used by riders, archers, or light skirmishers (vs.\u160 ?heavy front-line fighters).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Heater:} A medium shield shaped like a flatiron heater (and named for it). This is the traditional shape of many heraldic coats of arms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hoplite:} A large rectangular shield, very protective, but too heavy and clumsy for horsemen. Hoplite shields are often used resting on the ground. Generally rectangular in shape, but some are oblong and with rounded edges.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Kite:} A large, teardrop-shaped shield with a round top and pointed bottom, covering the body from shoulders to the knee or ankle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Large Round:} Identical to a round shield (below), only larger.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Primitive:} A shield used in primitive warlike cultures. Usually nothing more than a wooden framework with stretched leather over it, wicker, stiffened cloth, or even extremely rigid animal hide.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Round:} A round shield gripped inside the central boss. Unique in that it has thin unprotected edges which can be used to catch and break edged weapons with a special maneuver.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Riot:} A large rectangular clear plastic shield used by riot policemen. Light and tough, these enable shield walls and provide adequate defense against most attackers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Spiked:} A type of target with a central spike, a blade, or series of small spikes facing outward at the opponent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Target:} A round, medium-sized shield, common in many cultures. Usually made with a metal rim.\par}
