{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Tracking Reputation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player should track the sources of their character\u8217's Reputation and how much has been gained. Again, once Reputation has increased, it does not decrease. One merely becomes famous for different things. The gamemaster may, however, modify its chance of success (see {\b Reputation Modifiers}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Using Reputation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reputation is used in two ways: to identify someone, or to impress others (essentially saying \u8220"Do you know who I am?\u8221").\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Identifying Someone\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reputation may be used by the gamemaster to have nonplayer characters identify a character and the reason they\u8217're famous, or the players can roll to see if their characters have heard of a particular nonplayer character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Apply any appropriate Reputation bonuses or penalties (see {\b Reputation Modifiers}) and roll. This is different than usual skills or characteristics, in that rolls are against the subject\u8217's Reputation, not one\u8217's own. A character may try to augment their Reputation\line (or someone else\u8217's) with some sort of Communication skill, essentially talking someone up. If appropriate, a Knowledge or Lore skill might be used to augment a subject\u8217's Reputation if they are notable in that field.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the roll succeeds, the one whose reputation was rolled against is recognized. This likely affects how the nonplayer character reacts to the character. Better qualities successes yield more information. Failure means they\u8217're not known, and a fumble means a disastrous misunderstanding or case of mistaken identity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Someone can always try to deny who they are, but this grows increasingly difficult in more modern settings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel3 \b \fs24 Impressing Others\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reputation may be used to try to augment some Communication skills, if appropriate. Similarly, the gamemaster may allow the character to attempt to sway a nonplayer character\u8217's reaction to the character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use Reputation to augment another skill, roll against the character\u8217's Reputation:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Critical Success:} The character\u8217's Reputation adds a +50% bonus to the Communication skill to be used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Special Success:} The character\u8217's Reputation adds a +30% bonus to the Communication skill to be used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Success:} The character\u8217's Reputation adds a +20% bonus to the Communication skill to be used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Failure:} The character subtracts \u8211-20% from the Communication skill to be used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Fumble:} The character subtracts \u8211-50% from the Communication skill to be used.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Reputation Modifiers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Reputation is modified by the social distance of the audience. Usually, Reputation among family, place of employment, and neighborhood or home area is increased.\u160 ?On the other hand, Reputation diminishes with strangers and outsiders. Famous politicians, heroes, and celebrities might be completely unknown in distant places. Similarly, as time goes on, Reputations become less relevant. Add modifiers to a character\u8217's Reputation based on the observer\u8217's social proximity to them.\par}
