{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 11. Creatures\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This chapter provides a wide range of potential encounters, whether stalwart allies, loyal pets, vicious animals, or supernatural beings, as well as sample characters from the past, fantasy settings, the modern world, and the future. There is no difference rules-wise between a creature and a nonplayer character\u8212-the gamemaster characterizes them with description and roleplaying. They all follow the same rules as characters. However, they each represent an appropriate specimen and are not balanced in the same fashion as a player character. You can use these creatures \u8216'as is\u8217' or customize them as desired. No optional rules are used in these descriptions, though you can add or modify those as required (see Customizing Creatures and Nonplayer Characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All entries are described as \u8216'creatures\u8217' for convenience, though they might be human or unliving machines.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Format for Entries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Nearly every creature and nonplayer character follows the same format, though natural animals are in an abbreviated table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Name:} A generic title.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Description:} Brief information about the entry.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Characteristics:} Characteristics are presented in both a rolled range and an average (below). Some entries may have missing characteristics: it is either negligible or not applicable (see Creatures Without Characteristics).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Hit Points (HP):} Usually the average of SIZ and CON, for some entries, hit points may be figured differently, such as by POW or another characteristic. At 2 hit points a living creature is unconscious or otherwise incapacitated, and when it reaches or goes below 0, it dies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Movement Rate (MOV):} The primary means of movement is listed first. Creatures that are immobile have no MOV rate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Damage Modifier (DM):} The average for the average creature, if any. Recalculate if necessary for larger or smaller specimens.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Armor:} The armor value and type of armor, if any.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Attacks:} The attack type, the skill rating, and damage roll. For attacks, \u8216'+dm\u8217' means it is included, and \u8216'+\u189 ?dm\u8217' is when damage modifier is halved. Special combat abilities or conditions are noted here. All available attacks occur on the same DEX strike rank, unless specified otherwise. Generally, a claw attack does 1D6+dm, and a bite or horn does 1D3+dm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Skills:} The most relevant skills for an average encounter. For unlisted skills, humans have the base chances as a default, and additional skills should be determined by the gamemaster as appropriate (see Measuring Skill Ratings).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Powers:} Any powers an average specimen possesses, with types specified if necessary.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Power points are not listed but are equivalent to POW, where applicable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Creatures Without Characteristics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some creatures have a \u8216'\u8212-\u8217' in place of certain characteristics, meaning it is not applicable or has a value of 0. A creature without a characteristic cannot be affected by attacks against or conditions that affect that characteristic. Following are guidelines for creatures lacking specific characteristics:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Strength (STR):} A creature without STR cannot interact with physical objects, other than moving around them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Constitution (CON):} A creature without CON is immune to disease, radiation, poison, and other attacks requiring a resistance roll versus CON. It is never tired or fatigued. If it has SIZ and a material presence, its hit points are based on a different characteristic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Size (SIZ):} A creature without a SIZ lacks a physical body or has a microscopic one. It usually cannot interact with physical objects. Its hit points are likely based on CON, if it has any conventional hit points at all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Intelligence (INT):} Intelligent, sentient creatures have the normal range of INT, while animals and other non-sentient creatures possess \u8216'fixed\u8217' INT, generally a rating of 3\u8211-5, and are ruled by instinct, not reason. A creature with fixed-INT or with no INT is unaffected by powers that affect rational thought, though it may be affected by powers that manipulate emotions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Power (POW):} Even without POW, a creature may still have power points, but it does not regenerate them normally. Instead, it has some power or special ability letting it gain power points. Like living creatures, when it reaches 0 it is \u8216'unconscious\u8217' until it somehow regains at least 1 power point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Dexterity (DEX):} A creature without DEX is either immobile or is essentially stationary. If it has an attack, this this occurs on DEX rank 1.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Charisma (CHA):} Though all creatures have some form of CHA, it is rarely relevant to those not of the same species. If necessary, assign CHA based on 1D6 for plain and featureless creatures, up to 6D6+ for beings of divine beauty. If relevant, temporarily modify the CHA of a creature from another species by \u8211-10 while dealing with those outside its species.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Creatures as Player Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Players may want to experience the game by role-playing members of non-human races (this bestiary calls every nonhuman a \u8220"creature\u8221"), especially in settings where they\u8217're appropriate such as fantasy or science fiction. Wanting to play radically different creatures from humankind is a natural desire for role-playing, and if doing so fits the gamemaster\u8217's choice of setting, it should be allowed. However, certain creatures are easier to role-play than others.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Incomplete creatures (those without a value in one or more characteristics) are often too limited for enjoyment. Additionally, it may be less enjoyable for a player attempting to role-play a creature whose INT characteristic is generated with a roll of less than 3D6 (or 2D6+6).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The gamemaster may also discourage players from trying to role-play extremely powerful or philosophically unappealing beings, based on the setting and the particular campaign. {\b {\i For example,}} {\i in a fantasy setting where the majority of the player characters are playing elves, the gamemaster may not allow players to create trolls or dwarf player characters due to the strife that these (traditional) elf-enemies will bring to the group. Alternatively, a modern horror campaign where characters are fighting occult threats may be inappropriate for a demonic or angelic player character (despite their appropriateness to the setting).} Similarly, if the creature would create undue difficulties due to its very nature, such as extreme size, social enmity, or cultural elements, the gamemaster should disallow players to choose to run it as a player character race. All such decisions are at the gamemaster\u8217's discretion, and the player should ask the gamemaster if they are permitted to run a particular type of creature in the campaign.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These warnings aside, all creatures in this chapter are presented in as much detail as is required for use as a player character, though the gamemaster may wish to expand these entries to suit their particular setting and campaign. It is assumed in most cases that these statistics represent full-grown or mature versions of the creatures, meaning that the gamemaster should be able to limit the range of powers available to a player character version of the creature, with the assumption that in time, the player character creature may learn these additional powers and special abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To choose whether or not a particular creature is suitable for the campaign as a player character, the gamemaster should ask three questions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Is a player character version of this creature inappropriate for the campaign setting?}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Will this creature cause difficulties for other players or the course of the campaign?}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Will this creature unbalance the rest of the campaign?}\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the answer to any of these questions is \u8220"Yes\u8221", the gamemaster is advised to disallow the creature for use as a player character, or to do so with the most stringent of conditions or special allowances.\par}
