{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Customizing Creatures and Nonplayer Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It may be necessary to customize these creatures and nonplayer characters based on the power level of your game, or to better match the competency of the player characters. Here are guidelines for doing so and for managing these creatures and nonplayer characters as needed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It may make more sense for opponents to be of a higher caliber in one power level, such as a fantasy or superhero setting, while in other settings it might seem inappropriate or too challenging. In cases like these, the gamemaster may choose to increase the threat an opponent faces in another fashion, such as to increase the number encountered, or give them superior equipment, or other means as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Normal Campaigns\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The creatures and nonplayer characters in this chapter are geared for a normal campaign. They do not normally need to be adjusted, unless for a particular setting. Whenever adjusting characteristics, take note of any modified secondary characteristics (damage bonus, hit points, major wound, power points, etc.).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One thing to keep in mind is that even a little armor goes a long way. Adding 3 points of armor to an entity can make them challenging, and with more than +6 points they become very difficult to harm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Heroic Campaigns\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For a heroic campaign, here are ways you can adjust creatures or nonplayer characters to better suit heroic-level characters:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increasing the number of the creatures or nonplayer characters encountered by +25% or more.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adding one more extremely competent leader to any groups, perhaps built on the epic power level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Having them use superior tactics, be more cautious or aggressive, and taking better advantage of their terrain to gain tactical advantages and keep the player characters off-balance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increasing key characteristics by another D6, or a flat +3, keeping the rollable maximums intact.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Modifying combat-oriented and other relevant skills by +25% or multiplied by \u215 ?1.5.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adding more powers or increased efficacy in existing powers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Equipping them with better equipment, armor, weaponry, etc.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Epic Campaigns\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For an epic campaign, here are ways to adjust creatures or nonplayer characters to present more of a challenge:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Doubling the number that would be encountered by normal characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Giving them a leader at the superhuman power level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increasing characteristics by +6 or more, beyond racial maximums.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Doubling skill rankings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Having them use skills like Command and Strategy to even the playing field.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adding all-new powers or multiple power groups, or combining entries, with superpowers like Extra Hit Points an easy solution.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Giving foes the best equipment, armor, and weaponry available, whether power armor, magical artifacts, medical supplies capable of instant healing, etc. .\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Superhuman Campaigns\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For a superhuman campaign, the gamemaster may choose to adjust the following aspects of a creature or nonplayer character:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Numbers can be increased to the limit of what you feel comfortable handling, mixing up normal, heroic, and epic level nonplayer characters to vary the challenge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increasing characteristics far past the rollable maximums, using whatever powers to make these foes almost titanic in abilities and competency.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Tripling or even quadrupling skill ratings far above 100%.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adding less obvious powers like Extra Hit Points, Super Characteristics, Super Skill, etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Equipping opponents with exceptional arms, armor, and other gear, including magical or powered gear. They will also use this equipment tactically and to the best of their abilities.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 General Notes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As noted, these are just suggestions, and should be applied intelligently. Examine the player characters\u8217' abilities and use that as a basis for how tough to make meaningful opponents. Don\u8217't be afraid to scale back an encounter by having enemies flee, or increase the difficulty by having new enemies arrive, or introducing some environmental factor make things more difficult for everyone.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Gauging an enemy\u8217's relative strength against a player character\u8217's is a difficult art to master, and the flat distribution of dice results and unexpected tactics can make a potentially easy encounter a life-or-death struggle or end a climactic battle with a single first (and lucky) shot.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It\u8217's important, though, to always remember the main rule: have fun and make sure the players are having fun, too.\par}
